            "content": "# Design decisions\n\n## Why Bun instead of Node.js for CLI and daemon?\n\nBun was chosen for fast startup time and native TypeScript execution without a compile step. For a CLI tool, the time from `droid` invocation to first output matters. Bun also bundles well into a SEA (single executable archive), which simplifies distribution.\n\nThe tradeoff: Bun compatibility issues occasionally arise with npm packages written for Node.js. The bun-pty package (a Bun fork of node-pty) has had native library compatibility issues across platforms that required workarounds.\n\n## Why Ink/React for the TUI?\n\nUsing React for the terminal UI (`apps/cli/src/app.tsx`) was a deliberate choice to:\n1. Share component patterns with the web UI\n2. Reuse the same state management approach (hooks, context)\n3. Let frontend engineers contribute to the CLI UI without learning a different paradigm\n\nThe tradeoff: React in a terminal is more complex than traditional TUI libraries. The Ink abstraction layer occasionally has edge cases with layout and rendering that don't apply to DOM rendering.\n\n## Why a daemon instead of direct WebSocket connections?\n\nThe daemon (`factoryd`) acts as a stable broker between the CLI and frontends. Without it, the web UI would need to spawn and manage CLI processes directly — which is complex in a browser context. The daemon:\n- Manages CLI process lifecycle (spawn, monitor, kill)\n- Provides a stable WebSocket endpoint that multiple frontends can connect to simultaneously\n- Handles reconnection when the frontend refreshes\n\nThe tradeoff: three-layer communication (CLI → daemon → frontend) makes debugging harder than a direct connection.\n\n## Why extract daemon-core as a separate package?\n\n`@factory/daemon-core` was extracted from `apps/daemon` around early 2025 to allow the same WebSocket server and session management code to run in different contexts (local machine, remote CDE). The `apps/daemon` app became a thin wrapper that provides environment-specific configuration.\n\n## Why @factory/common for shared contracts?\n\nA single shared-contracts package ensures that types don't drift between the CLI, daemon, and frontend. If the CLI emits a notification with a field that the frontend doesn't expect, the TypeScript compiler catches it at build time (not at runtime). This pattern has prevented several integration bugs that would be difficult to catch in testing.\n\n## Why Statsig for feature flags?\n\nStatsig was chosen early (Nov 2024) for its org-level targeting — the ability to enable features for specific organizations without code changes. This is important for gradual rollouts and enterprise-specific features.\n\n## Why Firebase/Firestore as the primary database?\n\nFirebase Firestore was the initial database choice, selected for:\n- Realtime updates (useful for streaming session events to the frontend)\n- Low operational overhead (no database to manage)\n- Easy Firebase Functions integration\n\nThe tradeoff: Firestore's document model doesn't support complex queries, and costs scale with read/write operations.\n",
            "file_path": "/Users/jonathanlucuix-andre/Documents/test-repos/factory-mono/droid-wiki/background/design-decisions.md"
          },
