            "content": "# @factory/daemon-core\n\n**Active contributors (last 90 days):** factory-jerry, factory-sherry\n\n## Purpose\n\n`@factory/daemon-core` is the business logic layer for the Factory daemon. It implements session management, terminal access, WebSocket server, droid request routing, relay tunneling, automation scheduling, and code-server proxying. The `apps/daemon` application is a thin wrapper that wires this package to the runtime environment.\n\n## Directory layout\n\n```\npackages/daemon-core/src/\n├── index.ts                        # Main package export\n├── constants.ts\n├── types.ts                        # Core daemon types\n├── automations/                    # Automation runner and scheduler (18 files)\n├── code-server/                    # VS Code code-server proxy helpers\n├── droid/\n│   ├── droid-registry.ts           # Registry of active droid instances (~24k lines combined with test)\n│   └── types.ts\n├── relay/                          # Relay tunnel management (9 files)\n├── server/\n│   ├── daemon-server.ts            # Top-level daemon HTTP/WS server setup\n│   ├── web-socket-server.ts        # WebSocket server implementation\n│   ├── web-socket-request-router.ts# Routes incoming WS messages to handlers\n│   ├── websocket-auth-adapter.ts   # Authentication and session binding for WS connections\n│   ├── code-server-proxy.ts        # Proxies VS Code code-server traffic\n│   ├── tunnel-handler.ts           # Relay tunnel HTTP handler\n│   ├── auth/                       # Auth helpers for the server\n│   └── handlers/\n│       ├── droid-request-handler.ts     # **4,994 lines** — all droid/agent RPC methods\n│       ├── droid-request-handler.test.ts# **11,857 lines** — comprehensive test suite\n│       ├── terminal-request-handler.ts  # Terminal create/write/resize/close RPC\n│       ├── base-request-handler.ts      # Shared handler base class\n│       ├── authenticated-web-socket.ts  # Authenticated WS connection wrapper\n│       ├── command-sanitization.ts      # Sanitizes shell commands before execution\n│       ├── semantic-diff-prompt.ts      # Diff prompt generation for agent context\n│       └── types.ts\n├── services/                       # Internal daemon services (session state, etc.)\n├── terminal/\n│   ├── terminal-manager.ts         # PTY lifecycle: create, write, resize, close\n│   ├── terminal-state-tracker.ts   # Tracks terminal output and state\n│   ├── terminal-broadcaster.ts     # Broadcasts terminal events to WebSocket subscribers\n│   └── terminal-cleanup-scheduler.ts\n└── utils/                          # Daemon utility helpers (11 files)\n```\n\n## Key abstractions\n\n| Abstraction | Location | What it does |\n|-------------|----------|--------------|\n| `DaemonServer` | `server/daemon-server.ts` | Bootstraps the HTTP + WebSocket server; entry point for `apps/daemon` |\n| `WebSocketServer` | `server/web-socket-server.ts` | Manages WebSocket connections, heartbeats, and authentication |\n| `WebSocketRequestRouter` | `server/web-socket-request-router.ts` | Routes incoming JSON-RPC messages to the correct handler |\n| `WebSocketAuthAdapter` | `server/websocket-auth-adapter.ts` | Validates auth tokens and binds sessions to WS connections |\n| `DroidRequestHandler` | `server/handlers/droid-request-handler.ts` | All agent-related RPC methods (session init/load, model calls, tool execution, MCP, automations). **4,994 lines; test file is 11,857 lines.** |\n| `TerminalRequestHandler` | `server/handlers/terminal-request-handler.ts` | Terminal I/O RPC methods (create, write, resize, close, list) |\n| `TerminalManager` | `terminal/terminal-manager.ts` | PTY process lifecycle management |\n| `DroidRegistry` | `droid/droid-registry.ts` | Tracks active droid agent instances |\n| Relay | `relay/` | Manages outbound relay tunnels so remote machines can connect to the daemon |\n| Automations | `automations/` | Scheduled automation runner |\n\n## How it works\n\n`apps/daemon` creates a `DaemonServer` instance which starts the WebSocket server. When a client (the frontend or CLI) connects:\n\n1. `WebSocketAuthAdapter` validates the connection token.\n2. `WebSocketRequestRouter` dispatches each incoming JSON-RPC call to either `DroidRequestHandler` or `TerminalRequestHandler`.\n3. Handlers call into `TerminalManager`, `DroidRegistry`, and external services as needed.\n4. Results stream back as JSON-RPC responses or push notifications.\n\nThe `DroidRequestHandler` is by far the largest file — it owns everything related to running agent sessions: loading/saving sessions, dispatching LLM requests through `@factory/droid-core`, executing tools, relaying tool results, and managing the full agent turn loop.\n\n## Note on file sizes\n\n`droid-request-handler.ts` is **4,994 lines** and its test file is **11,857 lines**. When modifying this handler, read the surrounding context carefully; changes to session state or streaming logic ripple through many test scenarios.\n\n## Integration points\n\n- **`apps/daemon`** — imports and instantiates `DaemonServer` from this package.\n- **`packages/frontend`** — communicates with this package's WebSocket server via `DaemonSessionController`.\n- **`packages/droid-core`** — `DroidRequestHandler` imports tool definitions, LLM adapters, and streaming utilities from `@factory/droid-core`.\n- **`packages/common`** — all JSON-RPC method types (params and results) are defined in `@factory/common/daemon`.\n\n## Entry points for modification\n\n| What you want to do | Where to start |\n|---------------------|----------------|\n| Add a new daemon RPC method | Add the type to `@factory/common/src/api/daemon/types.ts`, then implement in `droid-request-handler.ts` or `terminal-request-handler.ts` and register in `web-socket-request-router.ts` |\n| Change terminal behavior | `terminal/terminal-manager.ts` |\n| Modify auth/connection logic | `server/websocket-auth-adapter.ts` |\n| Add a new automation feature | `automations/` |\n"