            "content": "# @factory/logging\n\n**Active contributors (last 90 days):** factory-sherry, Alvin Sng, Ricky S\n\n## Purpose\n\n`@factory/logging` provides centralized structured logging, typed error classes, metrics instrumentation, telemetry, and Sentry integration for the entire Factory platform. Every backend route, service, daemon handler, and CLI module imports from this package instead of calling `console.log` or throwing bare `Error` objects.\n\n## Directory layout\n\n```\npackages/logging/src/\n├── index.ts                    # Barrel export\n├── log.ts                      # logInfo, logWarn, logException, logError\n├── loggingConfig.ts            # Logging configuration (log level, Sentry toggle)\n├── defaultLogToConsole.ts      # Default console sink with structured formatting\n├── requestLocal.ts             # AsyncLocalStorage-based request context\n├── handleTelemetryIngest.ts    # Telemetry ingest endpoint handler\n├── telemetryClient.ts          # Telemetry client (sends events to Factory backend)\n├── outcome-recorder.ts         # Records structured outcome events\n├── utils.ts                    # Path extraction helpers (orgId, sessionId from URL)\n├── types.ts                    # LogMetadata, RequestLocalContext, TelemetryEvent types\n├── constants.ts\n├── enums.ts\n├── errors/\n│   ├── errors.ts               # MetaError + all ResponseErrorXxx classes\n│   ├── constants.ts\n│   ├── enums.ts\n│   ├── types.ts\n│   └── utils.ts\n├── metadata/\n│   └── types.ts                # LogMetadata, LogOptions\n├── metrics/\n│   ├── enums.ts                # Metric enum (~large: all metric names)\n│   └── types.ts                # MetricLabels type\n├── metrics.ts                  # Metrics class (increment, gauge, histogram)\n├── sentry/                     # Sentry adapter (setSentryAdapter, getSentryAdapter)\n├── tracing/                    # OpenTelemetry tracing helpers\n└── node/                       # Node.js-specific logging (OTEL, file transport)\n```\n\n## Key exports\n\n| Export | What it does |\n|--------|--------------|\n| `logInfo(message, metadata?)` | Structured info log; use for observability breadcrumbs |\n| `logWarn(message, metadata?)` | Warning log; use when something is unexpected but not breaking |\n| `logException(error, message, metadata?)` | Logs an error with full stack and metadata; use when locally handling an error (do not rethrow after calling this) |\n| `MetaError` | Internal error for bugs and unexpected states: `new MetaError('msg', { ...metadata })` |\n| `ResponseError400BadRequest` … `ResponseError503ServiceUnavailable` | HTTP-semantic error classes; thrown in API routes and caught by middleware |\n| `Metrics` | Class for incrementing counters, recording gauges, and histograms |\n| `Metric` | Enum of all tracked metric names |\n| `TelemetryClient` | Sends structured telemetry events to the Factory backend |\n| `OutcomeRecorder` | Records structured session/agent outcome events |\n| `loggingConfig` | Read/write the active logging configuration |\n\n## Error handling conventions\n\n*(Based on `docs/error-handling.md`)*\n\n**Rule 1 — Bubble by default.** Do not wrap code in `try/catch` unless you have a concrete recovery plan, a fallback return value, or need to translate to a different error type.\n\n**Rule 2 — Always use typed errors.** Internal bugs → `MetaError`. Non-200 user responses → the matching `ResponseErrorXxx` class. Never `throw new Error(...)`.\n\n**Rule 3 — Breadcrumbs, not noise.** Use `logInfo` / `logWarn` before risky calls to leave context. Never call `logError` (it is not the correct function; use `logException`).\n\n**Rule 4 — One or the other.** If you call `logException`, you are handling the error locally and must not rethrow. If you are rethrowing, do not log — just add breadcrumbs and rethrow.\n\n**Rule 5 — Preserve the original stack.** Re-throw the original error object. Only create a new error when the semantics genuinely change (e.g., translating a 3rd-party error to a `ResponseError404NotFound`).\n\n### Choosing the right error class\n\n| Situation | Throw |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Internal bug / unexpected failure | `MetaError` |\n| Bad request / validation | `ResponseError400BadRequest` |\n| Unauthenticated | `ResponseError401Unauthorized` |\n| Permission denied | `ResponseError403Forbidden` |\n| Resource missing | `ResponseError404NotFound` |\n| Conflict – retry later | `ResponseError409RetryConflict` |\n| Gone / deleted | `ResponseError410Gone` |\n| Semantic validation failed | `ResponseError422InvalidData` |\n| Rate-limited | `ResponseError429RateLimitExceeded` |\n| Not implemented | `ResponseError501NotImplemented` |\n| Service down / temporary | `ResponseError503ServiceUnavailable` |\n\n## Metrics\n\nUse the `Metrics` class to track counters and gauges. Metric names come from the `Metric` enum in `metrics/enums.ts`. Example:\n\n```ts\nimport { Metrics, Metric } from '@factory/logging';\n\nMetrics.increment(Metric.SessionCreated, { orgId, planTier });\n```\n\nThe `OutcomeRecorder` is used for structured session outcomes (success, failure, user abandon) and feeds into Factory's analytics pipeline.\n\n## OTEL / tracing\n\nOpenTelemetry tracing helpers live in `tracing/` and Node.js-only transports are in `node/`. These are intentionally not exported from the main `index.ts` to prevent Node.js modules from being bundled in browser environments. Import them from `@factory/logging/otel` when needed server-side.\n",
