            "content": "# WebSocket protocol\n\nThe daemon (`apps/daemon`) exposes a WebSocket server that the web and desktop clients connect to for real-time droid agent communication and terminal access. The protocol is [JSON-RPC 2.0](https://www.jsonrpc.org/specification) carried over WebSocket.\n\nThis is separate from the backend REST API. The backend handles authentication, session metadata, and billing; the daemon handles the live agent loop, stdin/stdout relay to the droid CLI process, and terminal multiplexing.\n\n## Connection\n\nThe daemon binds to loopback (`127.0.0.1`) on a fixed port:\n\n| Environment | Port |\n|---|---|\n| Production | `37643` |\n| Development | `41723` |\n\n**WebSocket URL:** `ws://127.0.0.1:<port>`\n\nThe daemon only accepts connections from `localhost` — it is not directly reachable from the internet. Remote sessions use an encrypted relay tunnel (`packages/daemon-core/src/server/tunnel-handler.ts`, `wss://relay.factory.ai`).\n\n## Authentication handshake\n\nAfter the WebSocket connection is established, the client sends a `daemon.connection.authenticate` request before any other method. The server validates the bearer token against the backend, then returns the authenticated user context. Requests sent before authentication is complete are rejected.\n\n```json\n// Client → Server\n{\n  \"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\",\n  \"id\": 1,\n  \"method\": \"daemon.connection.authenticate\",\n  \"params\": {\n    \"token\": \"<WorkOS access token or Factory API key>\",\n    \"clientVersion\": \"1.2.3\"\n  }\n}\n\n// Server → Client (success)\n{\n  \"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\",\n  \"id\": 1,\n  \"result\": {\n    \"userId\": \"user_abc\",\n    \"orgId\": \"org_xyz\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Session management methods\n\n| Method | Direction | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `daemon.initialize_session` | Client → Server | Spawn a new droid process for a session |\n| `daemon.load_session` | Client → Server | Reconnect to an existing session's droid process |\n| `daemon.add_user_message` | Client → Server | Send a user message to the active droid process |\n| `daemon.interrupt_session` | Client → Server | Interrupt the droid mid-execution (like pressing Ctrl+C) |\n| `daemon.close_session` | Client → Server | Close the session and clean up the droid process |\n| `daemon.kill_worker_session` | Client → Server | Force-kill a worker/sub-session |\n| `daemon.list_opened_sessions` | Client → Server | List sessions currently active on this daemon |\n| `daemon.list_available_sessions` | Client → Server | List sessions available for loading |\n| `daemon.search_sessions` | Client → Server | Search through session history |\n| `daemon.archive_session` | Client → Server | Archive a session |\n| `daemon.unarchive_session` | Client → Server | Unarchive a session |\n| `daemon.update_session_settings` | Client → Server | Update per-session configuration |\n\n## Terminal methods\n\n| Method | Direction | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `daemon.create_terminal` | Client → Server | Create a new terminal session (spawns a shell) |\n| `daemon.write_terminal_data` | Client → Server | Send keystrokes or data to a terminal |\n| `daemon.resize_terminal` | Client → Server | Notify the terminal of a window resize |\n| `daemon.close_terminal` | Client → Server | Close a terminal session |\n| `daemon.list_terminals` | Client → Server | List all active terminal sessions |\n\n## MCP (Model Context Protocol) methods\n\n| Method | Direction | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `daemon.add_mcp_server` | Client → Server | Register an MCP server |\n| `daemon.remove_mcp_server` | Client → Server | Remove an MCP server |\n| `daemon.toggle_mcp_server` | Client → Server | Enable or disable an MCP server |\n| `daemon.authenticate_mcp_server` | Client → Server | Run the OAuth flow for an MCP server |\n| `daemon.cancel_mcp_auth` | Client → Server | Cancel an in-progress MCP auth |\n| `daemon.clear_mcp_auth` | Client → Server | Clear stored MCP credentials |\n| `daemon.list_mcp_registry` | Client → Server | List available MCP servers from the registry |\n| `daemon.list_mcp_tools` | Client → Server | List tools exposed by connected MCP servers |\n| `daemon.toggle_mcp_tool` | Client → Server | Enable or disable a specific MCP tool |\n\n## File system methods\n\n| Method | Direction | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `daemon.list_files` | Client → Server | List files in a directory |\n| `daemon.search_files` | Client → Server | Search for files by name or content |\n\n## Other methods\n\n| Method | Direction | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `daemon.list_skills` | Client → Server | List installed droid skills |\n| `daemon.submit_bug_report` | Client → Server | Submit a bug report from the current session |\n\n## Server-pushed events\n\nThe daemon pushes events to the client without a prior request. Event payloads follow the JSON-RPC notification format (no `id` field).\n\n| Event method | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `daemon.droid_event` | Streaming output from the droid process (messages, tool calls, status changes) |\n| `daemon.terminal_event` | Terminal output data |\n| `daemon.session_notification` | Session-level status notifications |\n| `daemon.connection_status` | Connection health updates |\n| `daemon.request_permission` | Droid is waiting for user approval before executing a tool call |\n| `daemon.ask_user` | Droid is asking the user a question mid-execution |\n\n## Tool confirmation flow\n\nWhen the droid agent wants to run a tool call that requires confirmation, it pauses execution and sends a `daemon.request_permission` notification to the client. The client displays the approval UI, then responds with a `daemon.request_permission` result (accepted or rejected) identified by the original `toolUseId`. The droid resumes or aborts depending on the answer.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant D as Droid process\n    participant Srv as Daemon server\n    participant UI as Web/Desktop client\n\n    D->>Srv: request_permission {toolUseId, tool, args}\n    Srv->>UI: daemon.request_permission notification\n    UI->>UI: show confirmation dialog\n    UI->>Srv: result {toolUseId, selectedOption}\n    Srv->>D: permission result via stdin\n    D->>D: execute (or skip) tool\n```\n\n## HTTP endpoints\n\nThe daemon also exposes two plain HTTP endpoints on the same port:\n\n| Path | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `GET /health` | Basic health check: returns uptime and active session counts |\n| `GET /status` | Detailed status: daemon version, terminal sessions, WebSocket connections |\n\n## Client implementations\n\n| Client | Location |\n|---|---|\n| Web / Desktop (React) | `packages/frontend/src/features/daemon/DaemonSessionController.ts` |\n| CLI | `apps/cli/src/runner/streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.tsx` |\n",
