            "content": "# Security\n\nFactory's trust model is: the backend owns authentication and authorization, the daemon is an authenticated local process, and Firestore enforces per-document access rules as a second line of defence. API keys and integration tokens are never stored in plaintext — they are AES-encrypted before writing to Firestore. No credentials are logged.\n\n## Authentication\n\n**Provider:** [WorkOS AuthKit](https://workos.com/docs/user-management/authkit). Users sign in with email/password or SSO; WorkOS issues a short-lived JWT access token.\n\n**Backend validation (`apps/backend/src/app/api/_utils/middleware.ts`):**\n\n1. The Next.js edge middleware (`src/middleware.ts`) sets security headers and handles CORS on every request before it reaches any route handler.\n2. Route-level middleware (`src/app/api/_utils/middleware.ts`) extracts the `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header and validates it:\n   - If the token starts with `fk_` it is treated as a Factory API key and verified against Firestore (`packages/models/src/factoryApiKeys/handlers.ts`).\n   - Otherwise it is treated as a WorkOS JWT and validated via `packages/services/src/workos/verify-access-token.ts`.\n3. After validation the user ID, org ID (Firestore and WorkOS), and role are attached to the request context. Any request without a valid token returns `401`. Any authenticated user who is not affiliated with an org returns `403`.\n\n**Daemon authentication (`packages/daemon-core/src/server/websocket-auth-adapter.ts`):**\n\nWebSocket clients send a `daemon.connection.authenticate` message immediately after connecting. The daemon forwards the bearer token to the backend's `/api/auth/verify-token` endpoint and keeps the resulting user context for the lifetime of the connection. All subsequent messages on an unauthenticated connection are rejected.\n\n## Authorization\n\n**Route-level checks:** Most route handlers use `handleRouteMiddleware` (from `src/app/api/_utils/middleware.ts`), which resolves the org and user profile after token validation. Admin-only endpoints use `callAdminRoute`, which additionally checks that the user holds a `manager` or `owner` role.\n\n**Session ownership:** The backend verifies session ownership by querying Firestore. Firestore rules enforce this at the database level as well (see [Firestore rules](#firestore-rules) below).\n\n**Org membership:** WorkOS JWTs carry an `organization` claim. Firestore rules check `request.auth.token.organization == organizationId` to confirm that the caller belongs to the org they are querying.\n\n## Secret management\n\n**Integration OAuth tokens:** OAuth access and refresh tokens from GitHub, GitLab, Jira, Linear, Notion, Sentry, and Slack are AES-encrypted with a server-side key before being written to Firestore. Encryption and decryption go through `packages/services/src/utils/encryption/encryptionManager.ts`.\n\n**Third-party service keys (E2B, BigQuery, etc.):** Sensitive service credentials are stored in AWS Secrets Manager and loaded at runtime via `packages/services/src/services/aws/secrets.ts`. They are never written to environment variables at build time.\n\n**Environment variables:** App configuration uses the typed `@factory/environment` package, which validates and parses env vars at startup. Direct access to `process.env` is banned by an ESLint rule (`no-direct-process-env`), so all env access goes through the validated schema.\n\n**Factory API keys:** User-created API keys (`fk_…`) are stored in Firestore with a hashed copy for lookup; the raw key is only shown once at creation time.\n\n## Tool call confirmation\n\nWhen the droid agent wants to run a potentially dangerous tool (shell command, file write, etc.), it pauses before execution and sends a `daemon.request_permission` notification to the connected client. The client displays the tool name and arguments in the UI and waits for explicit user approval. The agent only proceeds if the user confirms; rejection causes the agent to skip or abort the tool call. This flow is implemented in `packages/daemon-core/src/server/handlers/droid-request-handler.ts` and `DaemonRequestPermissionResultSchema` in `packages/common/src/daemon/`.\n\n## Content Security Policy\n\n`packages/common/src/security/constants.ts` defines `BASE_CSP_SOURCES`, which is shared by the web app and desktop app. The policy:\n\n- Restricts `default-src` to `'self'`\n- Limits `connect-src` to the Factory API, Firebase, WorkOS, Sentry, and the daemon's localhost ports (`ws://localhost:37643`, `ws://localhost:41723`)\n- Sets `frame-ancestors: 'self'` to prevent clickjacking\n- Blocks `object-src: 'none'`\n\nThe CSP is applied by `src/middleware.ts` in the backend and by the Vite/Electron build config in the web and desktop apps.\n\n## Firestore rules\n\nAccess rules are in `firestore.rules`. Key patterns:\n\n| Resource | Read | Write |\n|---|---|---|\n| `organizations/{orgId}` | Org members only (`request.auth.token.organization == orgId`) | Manager or owner role |\n| `organizations/{orgId}/sessions/{sessionId}` (list) | Session owner only | — |\n| `organizations/{orgId}/sessions/{sessionId}` (get) | Session owner **or** session with `privacyLevel == \"organization\"` | — |\n| `organizations/{orgId}/sessions/{sessionId}/messages` | Same as session get | — |\n| `organizations/{orgId}/sessions/{sessionId}/plans` | Same as session get | — |\n| `organizations/{orgId}/userProfiles/{userId}` | Self only | Self only |\n| `organizations/{orgId}/agentReadinessReports` | Org members | Org members (append-only) |\n| `users/{userId}` | Self only | Self only |\n| `droids/{droidId}` | Nobody (read: false) | Creator only |\n\nFirebase Storage is locked down entirely: all reads and writes are denied (`allow read, write: if false`).\n\n## Dependency security\n\nThird-party dependencies are scanned for known vulnerabilities on every pull request using [Endor Labs](https://www.endorlabs.com/) software composition analysis (`.github/workflows/endor-labs.yml`). The scan targets the `factoryai` namespace and runs against the PR diff.\n",
