            "content": "# Security\n\n## Trust model\n\nFactory has several trust boundaries:\n\n| Boundary | Mechanism |\n|---|---|\n| User authentication | WorkOS SSO (AuthKit) |\n| API authorization | JWT tokens, validated by backend middleware |\n| CLI authentication | Factory API keys, stored in system keychain via keytar |\n| LLM access | Proxied through Factory backend — clients never hold LLM provider keys |\n| Firestore rules | `firestore.rules` in root restricts data access by user/org |\n| Storage rules | `storage.rules` restricts file access |\n\n## Authentication flow\n\n1. User signs in via WorkOS AuthKit in the web/desktop app\n2. WorkOS issues a JWT\n3. The JWT is included in all backend API calls\n4. Backend middleware (`apps/backend/src/middleware.ts`) validates the token\n5. User context is attached to the request\n\nThe CLI authenticates separately via a Factory API key stored in the system keychain. The CLI calls `apps/backend` with this key.\n\n## Secrets management\n\n- LLM provider keys (Anthropic, OpenAI, Google) are stored in backend environment variables — never in client code\n- Firebase credentials are in `.env.local` files (gitignored)\n- GitHub secrets store CI/CD credentials\n\n## Input validation\n\nThe daemon protocol uses Zod schemas for all JSON-RPC payloads (`packages/common/src/droid/schemas/`). The backend uses similar validation for API endpoints.\n\n## Tool execution safety\n\nThe CLI's `agent/tool-confirmation.ts` classifies tool calls by risk and requires user confirmation for potentially destructive operations (file writes, shell execution). Users can configure their autonomy level to auto-approve more or fewer operations.\n\n## Dependency security\n\nEndor Labs scans dependencies for vulnerabilities (`.github/workflows/endor-labs.yml`). Path-to-regexp and other high-risk transitive dependencies have version overrides in the root `package.json`.\n\n## Firestore rules\n\n`firestore.rules` in the repo root restricts read/write access by authenticated user ID and organization membership.\n\n## Internal apps\n\n`internal/web` uses WorkOS SSO exclusively — only Factory employees can authenticate. The boundary is enforced by WorkOS configuration and an ESLint `no-restricted-imports` rule preventing public packages from importing internal ones.\n",
