            "content": "# Fun facts\n\n## The longest files are test files\n\nThe largest files in the repository by line count are all test files:\n\n| File | Lines | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `droid-request-handler.test.ts` | 11,857 | The test file is 2.4× larger than the source |\n| `useLLMStreaming.test.ts` | 109,791 | Combined — the largest file by a wide margin |\n| `useLLMStreaming.integration.test.ts` | 67,011 | Integration tests for streaming |\n| `useChatKeyboardInput.ts` | 68,357 | A source file that rivals the test files |\n\nThe `useLLMStreaming.test.ts` at nearly 110,000 lines earns the title of largest file. Streaming LLM responses are apparently hard to test comprehensively.\n\n## The repo started as a Next.js app\n\nThe earliest commits (September 30, 2024) were from David Augustine Adams, bootstrapped from `create-next-app`:\n```\nInitial commit from Create Next App\nadd styled-components\nadd inter, ook, and supply-mono fonts\nstub useAuth hook\nbasic auth and redirect to login\n```\n\nIn about 18 months, it grew from a Next.js stub to a 5,000+ file monorepo shipping a CLI, daemon, desktop app, backend API, and more.\n\n## 1,600 commits in 90 days\n\nThe team ships ~530 commits per month, steadily. That's roughly 17 commits per day, 5+ days a week. The most commits in a single month in the tracked history: October 2025 with 610.\n\n## The CLI has been renamed\n\nIn January 2026, the CLI was renamed from `apps/factory-cli` to `apps/cli` (`chore(cli): rename apps/factory-cli to apps/cli #9092`). Git blame on any file in `apps/cli/` will show this as the most recent rename commit.\n\n## The feature flags file is the most actively edited \"constants\" file\n\n`packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` was changed 78 times in 90 days — more than once per day on average. Every new in-progress feature lands here first.\n\n## ink is pinned across the entire monorepo\n\nInk (React for terminals) is locked to version `6.7.0` via a root `overrides` entry. This prevents different parts of the repo from accidentally pulling in different Ink versions, which caused painful compatibility issues in the past.\n",
