          "type": "user",
          "text": "<system-notification>\nSkills provide specialized capabilities and domain knowledge. The user provided the following skill to provide detailed instructions on how to complete the task:\n<skill filePath=\"/Users/jonathanlucuix-andre/Documents/test-repos/factory-mono/.factory/skills/wiki/SKILL.md\">\n<name>wiki</name>\n<description>Generate comprehensive codebase documentation for a repository.\nUploads the wiki to view in the Factory app.\n (project)</description>\n# Wiki generation\n\nRead a repository, then produce a set of interconnected documentation pages that explain what the code does and how it fits together. The output is a `droid-wiki/` directory of markdown files, optionally uploaded to Factory via `droid wiki-upload`.\n\n## Quality standards (non-negotiable)\n\nEvery generated wiki must pass these quality gates. These are not suggestions; they are hard requirements. Each maps to a consensus criterion ID for traceability (see appendix).\n\n| Gate | Requirement | Criterion |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Information architecture | Top-down: overview → subsystem → component. ≥3 hierarchy levels. Landing page links to every subsystem. | M1 |\n| Code grounding | ≥80% of substantive claims reference a specific code path that resolves in the codebase. ≥3 code refs per page, ≥1 per major section. | M2 |\n| Uncertainty labeling | Every claim is `Fact:`, `Inference:`, or `Unknown:`. Zero unlabeled speculative claims. | M3 |\n| Internal link integrity | Every internal cross-link resolves to an existing page or section. Broken links = 0. | M4 |\n| Writing quality | No AI filler phrases. Every paragraph has ≥1 concrete fact. See §Human writing rules. | M5 |\n| Diagram quality | Diagrams add information beyond surrounding text. No decorative diagrams. All diagrams must parse without errors. | M6 |\n| Discovery before drafting | Repository survey and TOC planning must complete before any prose is written. | M7 |\n| Page metadata | `generatedAt`, `sourceRevision`, `skillVersion` present. `pageOrder` matches filesystem. | M8 |\n| Cross-linking | Each non-index page has ≥1 outbound wiki link. No dead-end pages. | S1 |\n| TOC on long pages | Pages with >5 sections or >300 lines include a table of contents. | S2 |\n| Related-pages section | Each page includes a \"Related pages\" or \"See also\" section. | S3 |\n| Freshness metadata | Each page displays generation date and source revision. | S4 |\n| Section-level refs | Code refs point to functions or classes, not just files, where possible. | S5 |\n| Fail-closed claims | Unverifiable behavior is never presented as fact. Missing evidence triggers `Unknown:` label with checked locations. | S6 |\n| Markdown-only default | HTML only when explicitly requested, renderer-supported, and accompanied by markdown fallback. | S7 |\n| Consent-gated upload | Remote upload requires explicit user confirmation via `AskUser`. Default is local-only. | N6 |\n\n## 1. Survey the repository (discovery before drafting)\n\n**Do not write any prose until this step is complete.** Build a comprehensive mental model of the codebase first.\n\n### 1a. Read discovery files\n\nRead these files when they exist:\n\n- `README.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `CONTRIBUTING.md` — project intent and conventions\n- `package.json`, `Cargo.toml`, `go.mod`, `pyproject.toml` — dependencies and scripts\n- `docs/` directory — existing documentation\n- Entry points (`src/index.ts`, `main.go`, `app.py`, etc.) — how the application starts\n- Directory listing of the project root and key subdirectories\n\n### 1b. Build the survey checklist\n\nComplete this checklist before proceeding to §2:\n\n- [ ] **What the project does** — its purpose in one or two sentences\n- [ ] **Major subsystems** — the 3–8 main areas of the codebase (e.g., API layer, database models, CLI, frontend components)\n- [ ] **Key data flows** — how data moves through the system (request → handler → database → response)\n- [ ] **External dependencies** — databases, APIs, message queues, third-party services\n- [ ] **Build and test commands** — how to build, test, and run the project\n- [ ] **Entry points identified** — main files that start the application or expose public APIs\n- [ ] **Configuration mechanism** — how the project handles config (env vars, config files, flags)\n\nIf any checklist item cannot be completed, mark it `Unknown:` with a note of what was checked.\n\n## 2. Plan the table of contents\n\nDesign a page tree before writing any prose. This step produces the wiki structure. The structure must follow top-down progressive abstraction: overview → subsystem → component.\n\n### Required tree shape\n\n```\ndroid-wiki/\n├── index.md                  # Project overview and quick-start\n├── architecture.md           # System architecture and data flows\n├── getting-started.md        # Setup, build, test commands\n├── domains/\n│   ├── index.md              # Domain overview\n│   ├── <domain-a>.md         # One page per major subsystem\n│   ├── <domain-b>.md\n│   └── <domain-c>.md\n├── api/\n│   ├── index.md              # API overview\n│   └── <endpoint-group>.md   # Grouped by resource or feature\n└── reference/\n    ├── index.md              # Reference overview\n    ├── configuration.md      # Environment variables, config files\n    └── data-models.md        # Database schemas, key types\n```\n\nAdapt the structure to the project. A small CLI tool might only need `index.md`, `architecture.md`, and a few reference pages. A large monorepo might need deeper nesting with per-package sections.\n\n### Tree constraints\n\n- Use lowercase filenames with hyphens: `getting-started.md`, not `GettingStarted.md`\n- Each directory must have an `index.md` that introduces the section\n- Maximum tree depth: 3 levels (e.g., `domains/auth/oauth.md`)\n- Maximum 200 pages per wiki run; prioritize the most important subsystems if the project is large\n\n### Section index rules\n\n- Every `index.md` must include a section map: one line per child page with a description and link\n- Order children by importance first, then alphabetically within the same tier\n- Do not create empty placeholder pages; fold thin sections into parent pages\n\n## 3. Generate pages top-down\n\nWrite pages in this mandatory order:\n\n1. `index.md` — project overview\n2. `architecture.md` — system-level view\n3. Domain pages — one per subsystem, most important first\n4. API pages — grouped by resource\n5. Reference pages — configuration, data models, glossary\n\n### Required page template\n\nEvery generated page must use this skeleton:\n\n````markdown\n# <Page title>\n\n> **Summary:** <2–4 sentences: what this page explains and why it matters.>\n\n_Last verified: <YYYY-MM-DD> against commit `<short-sha>`. Confidence: <high|medium|low>._\n\n## <Table of contents — required if page has >5 sections or >300 lines>\n\n## Overview\n\n## Key components / flows\n\n## Code references\n\n## Related pages\n````\n\n**Template rules:**\n\n- The summary block is required and must stay under 4 sentences.\n- The `Last verified` line is required on every page.\n- Confidence levels: `high` = >=90% of substantive claims are direct `Fact:` claims with resolving code references; `medium` = 60-89% direct `Fact:` coverage with limited inference; `low` = <60% direct `Fact:` coverage or key files/runtime context missing.\n- If a page exceeds ~1,200 words or becomes hard to scan, split it.\n- Hard page limit: **500KB**.\n\n### 3a. Read the relevant code\n\nOpen and read the actual source files for the section you are writing. Do not guess or hallucinate file contents. If a file is too large, read the parts relevant to the current section.\n\n### 3b. Write prose with grounding and uncertainty labeling\n\nExplain what the code does in plain language. Start with high-level purpose, then drill into specifics.\n\n**Grounding rules:**\n\n- Every substantive technical claim must reference a specific code path (file, function, or line).\n- Target ≥80% of claims grounded with verifiable code references.\n- At least 3 concrete code references per page, at least 1 per major section.\n- Prefer function/class-level references over bare file paths when possible.\n- Always use full repository-root-relative paths (e.g., `packages/common/src/daemon/constants.ts`) instead of bare filenames (e.g., `constants.ts`). Bare filenames cannot be resolved and fail verification.\n- Verify that every referenced file path actually exists in the repository before including it. If a file extension is `.ts`, do not write `.tsx` or vice versa.\n\n**Uncertainty labeling rules (fail-closed):**\n\nUse explicit labels when certainty varies:\n\n- `Fact:` statement confirmed by reading source files directly.\n- `Inference:` reasoned conclusion from multiple code signals, not directly verified.\n- `Unknown:` expected behavior that was not found in the current repository snapshot.\n\n**Fail-closed policy:** If you cannot find evidence for a claim, you must not present it as fact. Instead, label it `Unknown:` and list the locations you checked.\n\nExample:\n\n```markdown\nFact: `jobs/runner.ts` calls `processJob()` in a retry loop (line 42).\nInference: Delay growth appears exponential based on `retryDelayMs * 2`\nin `jobs/retry-policy.ts`.\nUnknown: Maximum retry count was not found. Checked `runner.ts`,\n`retry-policy.ts`, and `config.ts`.\n```\n\nBad (fail-open — never do this):\n\n```markdown\nThe worker retries failed jobs with exponential backoff up to 5 times.\n```\n\nThis states unverified specifics as fact without any code reference.\n\n### 3c. Add Mermaid diagrams (informative only)\n\nInclude diagrams only when they explain structure or flow better than text. Every diagram must add information not already stated in surrounding prose.\n\n**Allowed diagram types:**\n\n- `graph TD` or `graph LR` for architecture and flow diagrams\n- `sequenceDiagram` for request/response flows between services\n- `stateDiagram-v2` for state machines\n- `subgraph` blocks within `graph TD/LR` when grouping improves clarity\n\n**Diagram constraints:**\n\n- 5–15 nodes maximum; split larger diagrams into multiple focused ones\n- Label all edges with the action or data being passed\n- Diagram node names must match real component names from code\n- Add a one-line caption under each diagram describing what code paths it represents\n- Each diagram must parse without Mermaid syntax errors\n\n**Disallowed patterns:**\n\n- No decorative diagrams added \"for completeness\"\n- No unlabeled generic boxes like \"Service A\" (unless those are literal code names)\n- No diagrams that duplicate nearby text without adding structural clarity\n- No diagrams for simple relationships that a sentence explains faster\n\n**Minimum:** Include at least one Mermaid diagram on the architecture page. Include diagrams on domain pages only when they clarify data flows or component relationships.\n\n### 3d. Add file references\n\nPoint readers to actual source code using relative paths from the repository root:\n\n```markdown\nFact: The authentication middleware lives in `src/middleware/auth.ts`.\nIt validates JWT tokens and attaches the user object to the request\ncontext (see `attachUser()` at line 34).\n\nSee also:\n\n- `src/services/token-service.ts` — `createToken()` and `verifyToken()`\n- `src/types/auth.ts` — type definitions for auth payloads\n```\n\n**Citation density targets:**\n\n- At least 1 concrete code reference per major section\n- At least 3 concrete code references per page\n- Add line/function context for dense logic (example: `src/auth/guard.ts` → `validateToken()`)\n\nIf you cannot find the file that implements something, say so explicitly:\n\n```markdown\nUnknown: The retry logic is referenced in `config.ts` but the\nimplementation file was not found in the current codebase. Checked\n`src/`, `lib/`, and `utils/`.\n```\n\n### 3e. Cross-link pages and ensure retrievability\n\nLink between pages using relative markdown links:\n\n```markdown\nFor details on how the auth middleware integrates with the API layer,\nsee [API authentication](../api/authentication.md).\n```\n\n**Retrievability requirements:**\n\n- Each non-index page must link to ≥1 other wiki page (no dead-end pages)\n- Add a local table of contents for pages with >5 sections or >300 lines\n- End each page with a **Related pages** section containing 2–5 links\n- Every page must have at least one inbound and one outbound useful link\n\n### 3f. Freshness signals\n\nAt minimum, include a page-level freshness line near the top (part of the required template):\n\n```markdown\n_Last verified: 2026-03-03 against commit `abc1234`. Confidence: high._\n```\n\n## 4. Write the meta file\n\nAfter generating all pages, create `.wiki-meta.json` in the wiki directory root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"generatedAt\": \"2025-01-15T10:30:00Z\",\n  \"sourceRevision\": \"abc1234\",\n  \"skillVersion\": \"wiki@2.0.0\",\n  \"pageCount\": 12,\n  \"topLevelSections\": [\"index\", \"architecture\", \"domains\", \"api\", \"reference\"],\n  \"pageOrder\": [\n    \"index.md\",\n    \"architecture.md\",\n    \"getting-started.md\",\n    \"domains/index.md\",\n    \"reference/index.md\"\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n**Required fields:**\n\n- `generatedAt` — ISO 8601 timestamp of generation\n- `sourceRevision` — commit SHA used during generation\n- `skillVersion` — version of this skill file (e.g., `wiki@2.0.0`)\n- `pageCount` — total number of markdown files generated\n- `pageOrder` — ordered list of page paths relative to wiki root; must match files on disk\n\n**Integrity rules:**\n\n- `pageCount` must equal the number of `.md` files in the wiki directory\n- Every path in `pageOrder` must point to an existing file\n- `pageOrder` must have no duplicate entries\n- Files not listed in `pageOrder` are ordered after listed files using alphabetical fallback\n\n## 5. Upload (consent-gated)\n\nBefore running `droid wiki-upload`, use the `AskUser` tool to confirm whether\nthe user wants to push/upload the wiki remotely right now or keep it local first.\n\n**Default behavior:** Local-only generation. The wiki is written to `./droid-wiki` and no remote upload occurs unless the user explicitly approves.\n\nIf the user does not respond or declines, keep files local. Do not upload.\n\n### Standard upload (when user approves)\n\n```bash\ndroid wiki-upload \\\n  --repo-url \"$REPO_URL\" \\\n  --wiki-dir ./droid-wiki\n```\n\nArguments:\n\n- `--repo-url` — the repository URL (the remote origin, e.g., `https://github.com/org/repo`)\n- `--wiki-dir` — path to the directory containing the generated markdown files\n- `--cleanup` — (optional) delete the wiki directory after a successful upload\n\n### Remote-only upload (--no-local handling)\n\nWhen the user asks to generate the wiki without leaving files on disk:\n\n```bash\nWIKI_TMPDIR=$(mktemp -d)\n# Generate pages into $WIKI_TMPDIR\ndroid wiki-upload \\\n  --repo-url \"$REPO_URL\" \\\n  --wiki-dir \"$WIKI_TMPDIR\" \\\n  --cleanup\n```\n\nThe `--cleanup` flag deletes the `--wiki-dir` directory after successful upload. If the upload fails, the directory is preserved for retry.\n\n### Markdown fallback on upload failure\n\nIf `droid wiki-upload` fails, preserve the local `./droid-wiki` directory and inform the user. The local markdown files remain usable without remote upload.\n\n## Human writing rules\n\nWrite documentation that reads like a person wrote it. Technical docs are prone to AI-sounding patterns. These rules are mandatory.\n\n### Prohibited patterns with corrections\n\n1. **Cut inflated significance.** Do not write \"serves as a testament to,\" \"pivotal role in the evolving landscape,\" \"setting the stage for,\" or \"underscores the importance of.\" State what the thing does.\n\n   Bad: \"The authentication module serves as a critical pillar in the application's security landscape.\"\n   Good: \"The authentication module validates JWT tokens and attaches user context to requests.\"\n\n2. **Cut promotional language.** Do not write \"boasts,\" \"vibrant,\" \"rich,\" \"profound,\" \"showcasing,\" \"exemplifies,\" \"commitment to,\" \"groundbreaking,\" \"renowned,\" or \"breathtaking.\" Technical docs describe; they do not sell.\n\n   Bad: \"The codebase boasts a rich set of vibrant utilities that showcase the team's commitment to developer experience.\"\n   Good: \"The `utils/` directory has helpers for string formatting, date parsing, and retry logic.\"\n\n3. **Kill superficial -ing analyses.** Do not tack \"highlighting,\" \"ensuring,\" \"reflecting,\" \"symbolizing,\" \"showcasing,\" or \"contributing to\" onto sentences to add fake depth.\n\n   Bad: \"The service processes events asynchronously, ensuring scalability while highlighting the system's robust architecture.\"\n   Good: \"The service processes events asynchronously. It pulls from an SQS queue and can handle ~500 events/second per instance.\"\n\n4. **Avoid AI vocabulary words.** Replace these overused words with plainer alternatives: additionally, crucial, delve, emphasizing, enduring, enhance, fostering, garner, interplay, intricate/intricacies, landscape (abstract), pivotal, showcase, tapestry (abstract), testament, underscore (verb), vibrant.\n\n5. **Skip forced groupings.** Do not force ideas into groups of three for rhetorical effect. If there are two things, list two. If there are four, list four.\n\n6. **Do not use copula avoidance.** Write \"X is Y\" or \"X has Y\" instead of \"X serves as Y,\" \"X stands as Y,\" \"X represents Y,\" \"X boasts Y,\" \"X features Y,\" or \"X offers Y.\"\n\n   Bad: \"The config module serves as the central hub for environment variable management.\"\n   Good: \"The config module reads environment variables and exports typed constants.\"\n\n7. **Do not use negative parallelisms.** Avoid \"It's not just X, it's Y\" and \"Not only X but Y\" constructions.\n\n8. **Use sentence case in headings.** Write \"Getting started with authentication,\" not \"Getting Started With Authentication.\"\n\n9. **Cut filler phrases.** Replace \"in order to\" with \"to,\" \"due to the fact that\" with \"because,\" \"it is important to note that\" with nothing.\n\n10. **Be specific, not vague.** Replace \"industry experts believe\" with a concrete reference. Replace \"several components\" with actual component names. Replace \"various configurations\" with actual config options.\n\n11. **Avoid em dash overuse.** Use commas or periods instead. One em dash per page is fine; three or more is a pattern.\n\n12. **No chatbot artifacts.** Never write \"I hope this helps,\" \"Let me know if,\" \"Here is an overview of,\" \"Certainly!\", or \"Great question!\"\n\n## Optional interactive HTML policy\n\n**Default behavior:** Do not embed HTML widgets in wiki pages.\n\nAllow interactive HTML only when **all three conditions** are met:\n\n1. The user explicitly requests HTML content\n2. The target renderer is known to support HTML safely\n3. A plain markdown fallback is provided immediately below the HTML block\n\n**Fallback rule:** A reader on a markdown-only renderer must still get complete information without losing key content. The markdown fallback must convey the same data as the HTML widget.\n\n## File structure specification\n\n```\ndroid-wiki/\n├── .wiki-meta.json           # Generation metadata\n├── index.md                  # Project overview\n├── architecture.md           # System architecture with Mermaid diagrams\n├── getting-started.md        # Build, test, run instructions\n├── domains/                  # One page per major subsystem\n│   ├── index.md\n│   └── *.md\n├── api/                      # API documentation (if applicable)\n│   ├── index.md\n│   └── *.md\n└── reference/                # Configuration, data models, glossary\n    ├── index.md\n    └── *.md\n```\n\n**Rules:**\n\n- Every `.md` file must start with a level-1 heading (`# Title`).\n- Every directory must contain an `index.md`.\n- File names use lowercase with hyphens. No spaces, no uppercase.\n- `.wiki-meta.json` is for tracking purposes and is not uploaded as a page.\n- Maximum tree depth: 3 levels.\n- Maximum 200 pages per wiki run.\n\n## Appendix: Criterion-to-skill-to-check mapping\n\nThis table maps every consensus rubric criterion to its SKILL.md location and the planned empirical verification check.\n\n| Criterion ID | Priority | Criterion summary | SKILL.md location | Empirical check |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| M1 | Must | Top-down hierarchical IA (≥3 levels, landing links all subsystems) | §Quality standards table row 1; §2 \"Plan the table of contents\"; §3 generation order | Verify generated tree has ≥3 levels; index.md links to all subsystem pages |\n| M2 | Must | Code-grounded claims (≥80% with code path refs) | §Quality standards table row 2; §3b grounding rules; §3d citation density targets | Count code refs per page; resolve referenced paths against codebase; compute grounding percentage |\n| M3 | Must | Uncertainty labeling (Fact/Inference/Unknown, zero unlabeled speculation) | §Quality standards table row 3; §3b uncertainty labeling rules | Scan for Fact:/Inference:/Unknown: labels; flag unlabeled speculative claims |\n| M4 | Must | Zero broken internal links | §Quality standards table row 4; §3e cross-link rules | Parse all internal `[text](path)` links; verify each target file/section exists |\n| M5 | Must | Concise, human-sounding prose (no AI filler) | §Quality standards table row 5; §Human writing rules (12 prohibited patterns with examples) | Check for prohibited phrases from §Human writing rules; verify each paragraph has ≥1 concrete fact |\n| M6 | Must | Diagrams informative only (no decorative, must parse) | §Quality standards table row 6; §3c diagram constraints and disallowed patterns | Validate Mermaid syntax parses; verify diagrams add info beyond adjacent text; flag generic/decorative diagrams |\n| M7 | Must | Discovery before drafting (survey + TOC before prose) | §Quality standards table row 7; §1 survey check