            "content": "# Architecture\n\n> **Summary:** This page describes how the five major runtime components connect — CLI, daemon, backend, web/desktop, and the AI agent — and traces the data flow from a user prompt to an LLM response. Understanding this wiring is the prerequisite for contributing to any layer.\n\n_Last verified: 2026-03-04 against commit `1cfbf04239`. Confidence: high._\n\n## Table of contents\n\n- [Component overview](#component-overview)\n- [Communication layers](#communication-layers)\n- [Request lifecycle](#request-lifecycle)\n- [AI agent execution loop](#ai-agent-execution-loop)\n- [Deployment environments](#deployment-environments)\n- [Code references](#code-references)\n- [Related pages](#related-pages)\n\n## Component overview\n\nThe platform has three runtime tiers:\n\n1. **Client tier** — `apps/web` (browser), `apps/desktop` (Electron), or a terminal running `droid`\n2. **Daemon tier** — `apps/daemon` (`factoryd`), a long-lived Bun process that owns terminal sessions and Droid (CLI agent) processes\n3. **Cloud tier** — `apps/backend` (Next.js API), Firebase, external LLM providers\n\n```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    subgraph \"Client tier\"\n        WEB[\"apps/web (Vite)\"]\n        DESK[\"apps/desktop (Electron)\"]\n        CLI[\"apps/cli (droid TUI)\"]\n    end\n    subgraph \"Daemon tier\"\n        DAEMON[\"apps/daemon (factoryd)\\nBun WebSocket server\"]\n        DROID[\"droid exec process\\nspawned per session\"]\n    end\n    subgraph \"Cloud tier\"\n        BACKEND[\"apps/backend\\nNext.js API :3000\"]\n        LLM[\"LLM providers\\nAnthropic / OpenAI / Google\"]\n        DB[\"Firestore / Firebase\"]\n    end\n    WEB -->|\"WebSocket JSON-RPC\"| DAEMON\n    DESK -->|\"WebSocket JSON-RPC\"| DAEMON\n    CLI -->|\"stdin/stdout JSON-RPC\"| DROID\n    DAEMON -->|\"spawns + JSON-RPC\"| DROID\n    DROID -->|\"HTTPS\"| BACKEND\n    BACKEND -->|\"API calls\"| LLM\n    BACKEND -->|\"read/write\"| DB\n```\n\n_Diagram represents the communication paths documented in `docs/debugging-daemon.md` and `packages/daemon-core/src/server/daemon-server.ts`._\n\n## Communication layers\n\n### WebSocket JSON-RPC (client ↔ daemon)\n\nFact: The daemon exposes a WebSocket server on port 37643 (production) or 41723 (development), defined in `packages/common/src/daemon/constants.ts` via `WS_SERVER_CONFIG`. Connections use JSON-RPC 2.0 framing.\n\nFact: `packages/daemon-core/src/server/web-socket-server.ts` implements `DaemonWebSocketServer`, which handles three WebSocket upgrade types: `JSONRPC`, `TUNNEL`, and `CODE_SERVER` (see `WebSocketType` enum in `packages/daemon-core/src/server/enums.ts`).\n\nFact: The frontend connects through `packages/frontend/src/services/session/DaemonSessionController.ts` — an `EventEmitter`-based class (line 1) that wraps the WebSocket connection and dispatches notifications to Redux state.\n\n### stdin/stdout JSON-RPC (daemon ↔ CLI exec process)\n\nFact: When a session is initialized, the daemon spawns a `droid exec` subprocess. The CLI's entry point for this mode is `apps/cli/src/exec/streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.ts`. Communication goes over the subprocess stdin/stdout channel using the same JSON-RPC 2.0 schema defined in `packages/common/src/droid/`.\n\n### REST API (CLI/daemon ↔ backend)\n\nFact: The backend exposes REST endpoints under `apps/backend/src/app/api/`. The CLI uses `packages/droid-core/src/api/` (e.g. `fetch.ts`, `droid.ts`) to call these endpoints. The daemon's `ApiClient` (`packages/daemon-core/src/services/ApiClient.ts`) does the same for daemon-level operations.\n\n## Request lifecycle\n\nA user message follows this path:\n\n1. **User types a message** in the web UI or CLI\n2. **Frontend / CLI** sends `addUserMessage` JSON-RPC request to the daemon\n3. **Daemon** (`DaemonWebSocketServer`) routes the request to the `droid` subprocess via stdin\n4. **`streamingJsonRpcExecRunner`** in `apps/cli/src/exec/` receives the message and invokes the agent loop in `apps/cli/src/agent/messaging.ts`\n5. **Agent loop** calls the LLM (proxied through `apps/backend/src/app/api/llm/`) with the conversation history and available tools\n6. **LLM returns** a response, possibly requesting tool calls (file edits, shell commands, web search, etc.)\n7. **Agent** executes tools (`apps/cli/src/agent/tools.ts`) and streams results back over JSON-RPC notifications\n8. **Daemon** forwards notifications to the WebSocket client\n9. **Frontend** updates Redux state; the UI renders the streamed response\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant U as User\n    participant FE as Frontend/CLI\n    participant D as Daemon (factoryd)\n    participant E as droid exec\n    participant B as Backend API\n    participant L as LLM Provider\n\n    U->>FE: Type message\n    FE->>D: addUserMessage (JSON-RPC)\n    D->>E: stdin addUserMessage\n    E->>B: POST /api/llm (streaming)\n    B->>L: LLM API call\n    L-->>B: Token stream\n    B-->>E: SSE / stream\n    E-->>D: stdout notifications\n    D-->>FE: WebSocket notifications\n    FE-->>U: Render streamed response\n```\n\n## AI agent execution loop\n\nFact: The agent execution logic is split across two layers. `packages/droid-core/src/` provides the model-agnostic infrastructure (LLM providers, tool definitions, streaming, message handling). `apps/cli/src/agent/` wires this to the actual CLI runtime — tool implementations, permission handling, autonomy modes.\n\nFact: Tool definitions live in `packages/droid-core/src/tools/definitions/` and are split by type: `cli/` (Read, Edit, Execute, etc.), `file-tools/` (applyPatch, editFile), `mission/` (proposeMission, startMissionRun), and `web/` (fetchUrl, webSearch).\n\nFact: LLM provider routing (`packages/droid-core/src/llms/provider/router.ts`) dispatches to Anthropic, OpenAI, Google, or xAI backends based on the selected model.\n\n## Deployment environments\n\nThe platform supports four environments, resolved at runtime from the `NEXT_PUBLIC_ENV` variable:\n\n| Factory env | Statsig tier | Daemon default port | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `localhost` | development | 41723 | Local dev with `droid-localhost` |\n| `development` | staging | 41723 | Dev with `droid-dev` |\n| `preprod` | staging | 37643 | — |\n| `production` | production | 37643 | — |\n\nFact: The daemon port constants are defined in `packages/common/src/daemon/constants.ts` as `WS_SERVER_CONFIG.DEFAULT_PROD_PORT` (37643) and `WS_SERVER_CONFIG.DEFAULT_DEV_PORT` (41723).\n\nInference: Remote cloud development environments (CDEs) and E2B ephemeral sandboxes run the daemon the same way as local machines, using the `machineType` field (`MachineType.Ephemeral` vs `MachineType.Local`) to distinguish them, as seen in `apps/daemon/src/index.ts` (`resolveMachineType()`, line 113).\n\n## Code references\n\n- `docs/debugging-daemon.md` — canonical communication-layer diagram and debugging guide\n- `packages/daemon-core/src/server/daemon-server.ts` — `DaemonServer` class; wires `TerminalManager`, `DroidRegistry`, `HeartbeatService`\n- `packages/daemon-core/src/server/web-socket-server.ts` — `DaemonWebSocketServer`; handles WebSocket upgrades and routing\n- `apps/cli/src/exec/streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.ts` — JSON-RPC exec runner, entry point for `droid exec` subprocess\n- `packages/frontend/src/services/session/DaemonSessionController.ts` — WebSocket client, notification dispatch\n- `packages/droid-core/src/llms/provider/router.ts` — LLM provider selection\n- `packages/common/src/daemon/constants.ts` — port and connection constants\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [Getting started](getting-started.md)\n- [Daemon domain](domains/daemon.md)\n- [Droid CLI domain](domains/cli.md)\n- [AI agent core domain](domains/ai-agent.md)\n- [WebSocket JSON-RPC protocol](api/websocket-protocol.md)\n",
