          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nGood question. Features and systems are related but distinct:\n\n**Systems** are structural -- they map to code boundaries. \"The auth module,\" \"the daemon,\" \"the billing service.\" They answer \"how is the code organized and how does each part work internally?\"\n\n**Features** are functional -- they map to user-visible capabilities. \"Mission decomposition,\" \"MCP server integration,\" \"wiki generation,\" \"auto-update.\" They answer \"what can this product do and how does each capability work end-to-end?\"\n\nThe tension: a feature often cuts across multiple systems. \"Wiki generation\" touches the CLI (skill invocation), the backend (storage API), and the frontend (reader UI). No single system page covers it. A senior reading `systems/cli.md` would learn about the CLI's internals but wouldn't understand the wiki feature holistically.\n\nConversely, a system might support multiple features. The daemon supports sessions, terminal management, automations, relay connections -- each is a feature that happens to run through the same system.\n\nSome ways to handle this:\n\n**Option A: Features replace systems entirely.** Organize by capability, not by code structure. `features/wiki.md` covers everything about wiki from CLI to backend to frontend. Downside: you lose the \"where does this code live and how does it work internally\" perspective. Also hard when features share a lot of infrastructure.\n\n**Option B: Features and systems coexist as peers.** `systems/` for code-structural deep dives, `features/` for cross-cutting capability walkthroughs. A feature page links to the relevant system pages for implementation details. Downside: duplication risk, unclear where to put something that's both.\n\n**Option C: Features live inside systems.** Each system page has a \"features provided\" section. Works for features that are contained within one system, breaks for cross-cutting features.\n\n**Option D: Features are the top-level, systems are sub-pages.** `features/wiki/` contains `overview.md`, `cli-implementation.md`, `backend-storage.md`, `frontend-reader.md`. The system-level detail lives under the feature it serves. Downside: a system that serves 5 features gets documented in 5 places.\n\n**Option E: Systems stay structural, and cross-cutting features get their own top-level pages.** Most features map cleanly to one system and get documented there. The few that span multiple systems (wiki, missions, MCP) get dedicated feature pages that stitch the story together. This avoids a forced taxonomy for simple cases while handling complex ones.\n\nMy instinct is **Option B or E**. Most repos have features that map 1:1 to a module, so systems work fine. But the interesting features -- the ones a new engineer actually needs explained -- are the ones that span boundaries. Those deserve their own pages.\n\nThe real question is: for a generic wiki skill that works on any repo, can the LLM reliably distinguish \"this is a system\" from \"this is a cross-cutting feature that deserves its own page\"?\n\nWhat's your gut on this?",
