          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nMonorepos are tricky because they have multiple natural hierarchies competing for attention:\n\n**By package/app** -- `apps/cli`, `apps/daemon`, `packages/frontend`. This is how the filesystem is organized and how dependencies flow. But it doesn't tell you how things work together.\n\n**By feature/capability** -- wiki generation, sessions, missions, MCP. These cut across packages. A new engineer asking \"how does wiki work?\" doesn't care that it's split across `apps/cli/src/commands/wiki-upload.ts`, `apps/backend/src/app/api/v0/wiki/`, and `packages/frontend/src/features/wiki/`.\n\n**By team/ownership** -- who owns what. Often correlates with packages but not always.\n\n**By layer** -- frontend, backend, shared libraries, infrastructure. Horizontal slices vs the vertical slices above.\n\nThe problem with forcing one hierarchy: if you organize by package, cross-cutting features are invisible. If you organize by feature, you lose the \"I need to understand how `packages/daemon-core` works internally\" use case. A senior debugging the daemon doesn't want to read 6 feature pages to piece together what `daemon-core` does.\n\nFor factory-mono specifically, think about what questions people actually ask:\n\n- \"How does the daemon work?\" → system/package question\n- \"How does wiki generation work end-to-end?\" → feature question\n- \"I need to add a new tool to the CLI\" → pattern/convention question\n- \"What's the difference between `@factory/frontend` and `apps/web`?\" → code organization question\n- \"How do sessions flow from the browser to the LLM?\" → architecture/feature hybrid\n\nA monorepo wiki probably needs both lenses. The question is which is primary and which is secondary.\n\nOne thought: in a monorepo, the **packages are already documented by their own code** -- you can read `packages/daemon-core/src/` to understand the daemon. What's missing is the connective tissue. How do the packages compose into features? What are the boundaries and contracts? That's the value a wiki adds over just reading the source.\n\nSo maybe for monorepos specifically, features should be the primary lens in `systems/`, with package-level detail as supporting material within each feature page or in `reference/`. The package catalog page already tells you \"here are all the packages and what they do.\" The systems/features pages tell you \"here's how they combine to do something useful.\"\n\nBut then for a single-app repo, there are no packages to compose -- the \"systems\" are just modules within one app, and features might not be meaningfully distinct from systems.\n\nSo maybe the answer is: the skill doesn't prescribe whether `systems/` contains package-oriented pages or feature-oriented pages. It lets the survey phase determine which lens makes more sense for the repo. For monorepos, lean toward features. For single-app repos, lean toward modules/subsystems. The skill just says \"organize by the most useful unit of understanding for a reader.\"\n\nDoes that track, or do you think monorepos should explicitly have both?",
