          "text": "\n\nThat's clean. Three possible lenses, use whichever combination fits:\n\n**Applications** -- the deployable units. `apps/cli`, `apps/daemon`, `apps/web`. Each has its own entry point, runtime, and deployment. Relevant when the repo ships multiple distinct things. A single-app repo wouldn't have this section at all.\n\n**Systems** -- the internal building blocks. `packages/daemon-core`, `packages/droid-core`, the auth module, the billing service. Structural, code-oriented, \"how does this piece work internally.\" Relevant for almost any non-trivial repo.\n\n**Features** -- the cross-cutting capabilities. Wiki generation, mission decomposition, MCP integration. User-visible or developer-visible things that span multiple systems or applications. Relevant when the interesting story is how pieces compose, not how individual pieces work.\n\nFor factory-mono, you'd probably get all three:\n- `applications/` -- cli, daemon, web, desktop, backend\n- `systems/` -- daemon-core, droid-core, core-ui, common\n- `features/` -- sessions, wiki, missions, MCP, automations\n\nFor a small Express API, you'd probably get just:\n- `systems/` -- auth, database, routes, middleware\n\nFor a CLI tool with plugins:\n- `systems/` -- core, parser, config\n- `features/` -- plugin system, auto-update\n\nThe LLM surveys the repo, identifies what exists, and decides which combination of the three lenses would be most useful. No forced structure, just a menu of organizational tools.\n\nOne concern: overlap. In factory-mono, the daemon is both an application (`apps/daemon`) and closely tied to a system (`packages/daemon-core`). Do both pages exist? Does one reference the other? The application page covers \"how to run it, its startup sequence, its config\" and the system page covers \"how the internals work, key abstractions, extension points\"?\n\nThat actually might be the right split. Application pages are operational (deploy, configure, run). System pages are structural (how