          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nPackages makes sense as a fourth lens. It's distinct from systems -- a \"system\" is a conceptual unit (auth, billing), a \"package\" is a literal npm/cargo/pip workspace. In a monorepo they often align but not always. `@factory/common` isn't a system, it's a shared dependency. `@factory/logging` isn't a system either. But both deserve documentation. A packages section would cover what each package exports, its API surface, when to use it vs alternatives, and its relationship to other packages.\n\nThough now I'm wondering if packages is just a reference page (the catalog we already have) rather than a deep-dive section. The interesting packages that warrant their own pages are probably already covered as systems. The utility packages (`common`, `logging`, `utils`, `environment`) are better served by a page that says \"here's what's available and how to use it\" -- more reference than narrative.\n\nOn primitives -- this is interesting and I haven't seen it done well anywhere. You're talking about the foundational domain objects that show up everywhere:\n\n- **Session** -- what is it, what fields does it have, where is it created, who owns it, what states can it be in, where is the source of truth\n- **Organization** -- what does it represent, how does it relate to users, where is it stored\n- **User** -- auth identity vs profile vs permissions, how it flows through the system\n- **Message** -- the conversation unit, its content blocks, its lifecycle\n- **Tool** -- definition, execution, result shape\n- **Machine** -- local vs ephemeral, how it's identified\n\nThese aren't features (you don't \"use\" a session the way you use wiki generation). They aren't systems (there's no \"session system,\" sessions flow through many systems). They're the vocabulary of the codebase made concrete. The types that every contributor needs to understand because they show up in every function signature.\n\nThis is actually what the glossary page was trying to be, but more useful. A glossary gives you a one-liner. A primitives page gives you the full picture: the type definition, its lifecycle, its state machine, where it lives in the database, how it flows between systems, the invariants that must hold.\n\nFor factory-mono:\n- `primitives/session.md` -- FactoryDroidSession, its states, how it flows from frontend through daemon to CLI, what gets persisted\n- `primitives/message.md` -- FactoryDroidMessage, content blocks, roles, how streaming builds them incrementally\n- `primitives/tool.md` -- FactoryTool, LLMToolSpec, how tools are defined vs registered vs executed\n- `primitives/machine.md` -- local vs ephemeral, machine ID, how the daemon resolves machine type\n\nThis is the stuff that takes weeks to absorb by reading code. Having it in one place per concept would be genuinely valuable.\n\nSo the full set of organizational lenses would be:\n\n1. **Applications** -- deployable units (when the repo ships multiple things)\n2. **Systems** -- internal architectural building blocks\n3. **Features** -- cross-cutting capabilities\n4. **Packages** -- workspace-level documentation (monorepo utility packages)\n5. **Primitives** -- foundational domain objects that appear everywhere\n\nBut five lenses feels like a lot. For any given repo, you'd use 2-3 of them. The concern is: does the LLM have enough signal from surveying the code to pick the right combination? And can it reliably distinguish \"this is a system\" from \"this is a feature\" from \"this is a primitive\"?\n\nThe heuristic might be:\n- If it has its own entry point and deployment, it's an **application**\n- If it's a package that other packages import, it's a **package** (or just reference material)\n- If it's a module with internal logic and clear boundaries, it's a **system**\n- If it's a type/concept that appears in 3+ systems, it's a **primitive**\n- If understanding it requires tracing through multiple systems, it's a **feature**\n\nDoes that feel right, or is the packages lens redundant with reference material?",
