          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nThe distinction I'd draw:\n\n**Systems** implies internal architectural components. The auth system, the state management system, the build system. It's about machinery -- how things work under the hood.\n\n**Services** implies runtime processes that do things for other processes. The API service, the daemon service, the relay service. It carries a \"running process with an interface\" connotation.\n\nFor factory-mono, \"systems\" feels right for `daemon-core`, `droid-core`, the terminal manager -- these are internal building blocks. \"Services\" feels right for things like the heartbeat service, the API client, the update service -- things that run and serve other components.\n\nBut honestly, in practice people use them interchangeably and the distinction is fuzzy. A team that calls everything \"services\" wouldn't benefit from being told their code is actually organized into \"systems.\"\n\nI think the right move is: make them aliases. The skill lists both as options for the same lens. The LLM picks whichever term matches the repo's own vocabulary. If the codebase has a `services/` directory, call them services. If it has `systems/` or `modules/` or `core/`, match that. If it has no clear convention, default to one (probably systems since it's broader).\n\nThe point of the section is the same regardless of label: \"here are the major internal building blocks, one page each, here's how they work.\" Whether you call that systems or services or modules is a naming choice, not a structural one.\n\nSame logic could apply to applications vs services actually. In some repos, what we're calling \"applications\" are called \"services\" (microservice repos). The skill should probably say: \"identify the major units and use whatever term the repo already uses. If the repo has no convention, here's the default.\"\n\nSo rather than five rigid lens names, it's more like five *concepts* with flexible labels:\n\n| Concept | Default label | Also called |\n|-