          "text": "\n\nA guided tour inside `overview/` makes sense -- it's introductory material, and a tour is the ultimate introduction. Here's how I'd think about it:\n\n**What it is:** A narrative-driven page that tells a new engineer \"read these files in this order to understand the codebase.\" Not a list of links -- an actual story with context for each stop.\n\n**How it differs from architecture:** Architecture says \"here are the boxes and arrows.\" A guided tour says \"start at the front door, walk through the hallway, peek into the kitchen, then go upstairs.\" It's opinionated about sequence and attention.\n\n**Possible format:**\n\n```markdown\n# Guided tour\n\nA walkthrough of the codebase for your first day. Follow these stops in order.\nEach one builds on the previous.\n\n## Stop 1: The entry point\nStart at `src/index.ts`. This is where the application boots...\n[what to notice, what to ignore for now]\n\n## Stop 2: The request lifecycle\nOpen `src/api/router.ts`. Every HTTP request flows through here...\n[trace one request from start to finish]\n\n## Stop 3: The data layer\nNow look at `src/models/user.ts`. This is the most-imported model...\n[how data is structured, what patterns to recognize]\n\n## Stop 4: The config system\nBefore going deeper, understand `src/config/index.ts`...\n[how the app knows what environment it's in]\n\n## Stop 5: Your first feature\nLook at `src/features/auth/`. This is a good example of how features\nare structured. When you build your first feature, copy this pattern...\n```\n\n**Key design questions:**\n- How many stops? Too few and it's useless, too many and nobody finishes it. I'd say 5-8 stops for most repos, up to 12 for large monorepos.\n- Should it link to wiki pages or source files? Both -- link to the actual source file for each stop, and cross-link to the relevant wiki page for deeper reading.\n- Should it be one page or could it be a directory? One page keeps it linear and readable. A directory breaks the \"follow this path\" feeling.\n\nI think this works as `overview/guided-tour.md` -- a single page, 5-8 stops, each stop pointing to a real file with 2-3 sentences of context and a link to the deeper wiki page. Want me to add it to the skill?",
          "timestamp": "2026-03-11T05:33:44.412Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "Is this actually helpful?",
          "timestamp": "2026-03-11T05:38:31.813Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nHonestly, probably not.\n\nA guided tour sounds appealing in theory, but in practice:\n\n1. **Engineers don't read linearly.** They land in the codebase with a task (\"fix this bug\", \"add this feature\") and grep their way to the relevant code. Nobody sits down and reads files 1 through 8 in order.\n\n2. **Architecture already covers this.** The architecture page with its Mermaid diagrams shows you the system structure and data flows. A guided tour is just architecture written as a narrative instead of a diagram -- same information, more words.\n\n3. **Getting-started already covers the onboarding angle.** \"How do I set up, build, and run this\" is what a new engineer actually needs on day one. Not \"read these 8 files in order.\"\n\n4. **It would be the fastest page to go stale.** File paths change, features get refactored, entry points move. Every stop in the tour becomes a maintenance liability.\n\nThe only scenario where a guided tour genuinely helps is a codebase so unusual that you literally can't figure out where to start by looking at the directory structure. That's rare.\n\nSkip it. The overview section is already tight with index, architecture, getting-started, and glossary.",
          "timestamp": "2026-03-11T05:38:36.970Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "Would a \"How to test\" section after \"How to contribute\" be helpful or no",
          "timestamp": "2026-03-11T05:40:31.239Z"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nThere's already a `how-to-contribute/testing.md` page that covers \"frameworks, patterns, how to run, mock, and cover.\" So the content is there -- the question is whether it deserves promotion to its own top-level section.\n\nI don't think so. Testing is part of contributing. When an engineer asks \"how do I test this?\", it's always in the context of a change they're making -- which is the how-to-contribute workflow. Pulling testing out into its own section would fragment the \"I'm contributing, what do I need to know?\" story.\n\nThe exception would be if the repo has a genuinely complex test infrastructure -- custom test frameworks, multiple test tiers (unit/integration/e2e/contract), test data generation systems, flaky test management. But even then, that's better as a deeper `how-to-contribute/testing/` directory with sub-pages than a separate top-level section.\n\nNo change needed.",
