        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "\n\nThat's a good challenge to my earlier dismissal. Let me reconsider.\n\nA runbook answers \"something is happening, what do I do?\" -- which is genuinely different from both \"orient me\" (overview) and \"I want to contribute\" (how-to-contribute). And right now, runbook knowledge either lives in someone's head, a random Notion page, or a Slack thread from 6 months ago. The wiki could be the canonical place for it.\n\nBut here's the thing -- `how-to-contribute/debugging.md` already partially covers this. The question is whether debugging a local dev issue and responding to a production incident are different enough to warrant separation.\n\nThey are. \"My tests are failing locally\" and \"the API is returning 500s in production\" are completely different workflows, different tools, different urgency.\n\nSo there's a real gap: **operational knowledge**. What to do when things go wrong in production. Not deployment (how to ship), not debugging (local dev issues), but incident response and operational understanding.\n\nBut I'd push back on making it a full runbook. A proper runbook has step-by-step checklists, escalation paths, PagerDuty links -- that's living operational docs that belong in your incident management tool. What the wiki can do is provide the **context** an on-call engineer needs: what are the failure modes, what metrics to watch, what are the known fragile areas, where are the circuit breakers.\n\nThat fits naturally as a conditional section -- only relevant for repos that actually run in production (not libraries, CLI tools, etc.).",
