            "content": "# TUI rendering\n\nThe interactive CLI uses [Ink](https://github.com/vadimdemedes/ink), a React-based renderer for terminal UIs. Ink maps React components to terminal output using the same reconciler model as React DOM — but writing to `stdout` with ANSI escape codes instead of a browser DOM.\n\n## How the TUI boots\n\n1. `src/index.ts` detects no subcommand arguments.\n2. It calls `src/main.tsx`, which calls `render()` from Ink with `<App />` as the root.\n3. `src/app.tsx` renders the full TUI shell.\n\n## Component tree\n\nThe root `App` component in `src/app.tsx` owns:\n\n- The active session view (message list, input box, tool output panels)\n- Navigation and keyboard shortcut handling\n- Connection status indicators\n- Command palette\n\nSub-components live in `src/components/`, organized by feature area. Key areas:\n\n| Directory | Contents |\n|-----------|----------|\n| `src/components/message/` | Message rendering (user, assistant, tool calls) |\n| `src/components/input/` | The chat input box and autocomplete |\n| `src/components/tools/` | Per-tool output renderers |\n| `src/components/session/` | Session metadata and navigation |\n| `src/components/status/` | Status bar and connection indicator |\n\n## Keyboard handling\n\nInk processes keyboard input via `useInput` hooks. The CLI intercepts:\n\n- `Ctrl+C` — interrupt / cancel\n- `Ctrl+Z` — background the process\n- Arrow keys — scroll message history\n- `/` — open the command palette\n\n## Sounds\n\n`src/sounds/` contains audio assets played on certain events (e.g., task completion). These are loaded as embedded assets in the SEA bundle.\n\n## i18n\n\n`src/i18n/` contains localization strings. Language switching is available via the `/language` command (backed by `src/commands/language.ts`).\n\n## Terminal compatibility\n\nThe TUI is built for modern terminals (macOS Terminal, iTerm2, VS Code integrated terminal, Windows Terminal). It falls back gracefully when features like color or wide characters are unavailable.\n\n## E2E testing the TUI\n\nTests in `apps/cli/e2e-tests/` use `@microsoft/tui-test` to launch the CLI in a real terminal, send keystrokes, and assert on the rendered output. Config is at `apps/cli/tui-test.config.ts`.\n\n```ts\n// Example shape of a TUI test\nconst { screen } = await tui.launch({ command: 'droid' });\nawait screen.type('hello world');\nawait screen.press('Enter');\nawait screen.waitFor('Droid');\n```\n",
