            "content": "# Session management\n\nA session is the central unit of interaction with Droid. It holds a message history, the working directory context, tool call results, and metadata like title and tags. Sessions persist across UI connections.\n\n## Session lifecycle\n\n```mermaid\nstateDiagram-v2\n    [*] --> Creating: user starts new session\n    Creating --> Active: session.initialize completes\n    Active --> Running: user sends message\n    Running --> Active: agent finishes turn\n    Running --> Interrupted: user sends interrupt\n    Interrupted --> Active: ready for next message\n    Active --> [*]: user closes session\n```\n\n## Where sessions live\n\nSessions are stored in **Firestore** on the backend. The daemon keeps an in-memory representation of the currently active session during a run.\n\nThe session data model is defined in `packages/common/src/session/`. Key fields:\n\n- `sessionId` — unique identifier\n- `title` — display name (auto-generated or user-set)\n- `messageTree` — the full message history\n- `workingDirectory` — the directory context for tool calls\n- `droidConfig` — which droid configuration is active\n- `createdAt`, `updatedAt` — timestamps\n\n## Session initialization\n\nWhen a client calls `session.initialize`:\n\n1. The daemon checks if a session with the given ID already exists.\n2. If yes, it loads the session from the backend (Firestore) and resumes.\n3. If no, it creates a new session record on the backend.\n4. The daemon establishes the in-memory session state.\n\n## Message flow within a session\n\nWhen the user sends a message:\n\n1. The client sends `session.sendMessage` via JSON-RPC.\n2. The daemon appends the message to the session's message tree.\n3. The daemon calls the backend to run an LLM completion with the full message history + tools.\n4. The backend streams token events back.\n5. The daemon forwards token events to the client as JSON-RPC notifications.\n6. When the LLM makes tool calls, the daemon executes them and appends results.\n7. The loop continues until the LLM emits a stop reason.\n\n## Session state in the frontend\n\nOn the frontend (`packages/frontend`), session state lives in the Redux `assembly` slice. `DaemonSessionController.ts` manages the WebSocket connection and dispatches JSON-RPC notifications into Redux actions.\n\nThe session view in `packages/frontend/src/features/sessions/` renders from this Redux state.\n\n## Session persistence\n\nSession data is saved incrementally to Firestore as messages and tool results arrive. This means sessions survive network interruptions — when the client reconnects, it loads the latest state from the backend.\n\n## Multi-client sessions\n\nThe daemon supports multiple simultaneous clients on a single session. Each client receives the same notifications. This is how the desktop app can show the session while the CLI is also running.\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [daemon-core](../packages/daemon-core.md) — the in-memory session runtime\n- [JSON-RPC communication](./json-rpc-communication.md) — the protocol for session operations\n- [frontend package](../packages/frontend.md) — the Redux session state\n- [Backend API routes](../apps/backend/api-routes.md) — `/api/sessions` endpoints\n",
