            "content": "# Security\n\n## Authentication\n\n**WorkOS** handles all authentication. The backend at `apps/backend/src/services/workos/` integrates with WorkOS for:\n\n- OAuth SSO login\n- JWT issuance and validation\n- User and organization management\n- Directory sync (SCIM)\n\nThe Next.js middleware at `apps/backend/src/middleware.ts` validates WorkOS JWTs on every request and attaches user context.\n\n## API keys\n\nProgrammatic access uses API keys. Key management lives in `apps/backend/src/services/integrations/` and the settings API. Keys are hashed before storage — the plaintext is shown only once at creation time.\n\n## Credentials storage (CLI)\n\nThe CLI stores the user's auth token in the OS keychain using `keytar`. The keytar binary is embedded in the CLI bundle (`apps/cli/src/utils/keytarEmbedded.ts`) to avoid runtime dependency issues.\n\n## Authorization\n\nThe backend enforces authorization at the service layer. Most operations are scoped to the authenticated user's organization. Role-based access (admin vs. member) is checked via WorkOS roles.\n\n## Environment variables\n\nEnvironment variables are accessed through the `@factory/environment` package, which exports typed constants. Direct `process.env` access is banned by ESLint (`no-direct-process-env` rule). This prevents accidental exposure of secrets in logs or error messages.\n\nSensitive environment variables (API keys, database credentials, OAuth secrets) are stored in:\n- Vercel environment settings (backend/web deployment)\n- GitHub Actions secrets (CI/CD workflows)\n- `.env.local` files (local development, gitignored)\n\n## Firestore security rules\n\n`firestore.rules` at the repo root defines read/write rules for the Firestore database. Rules enforce per-user and per-organization data isolation.\n\n## Firebase Storage rules\n\n`storage.rules` controls access to Firebase Storage buckets.\n\n## LLM proxy security\n\nThe backend LLM proxy (`apps/backend/src/app/api/llm/`) validates all requests before forwarding to upstream providers. It checks that:\n\n- The user is authenticated\n- The user's organization has sufficient quota\n- The requested model is available for the user's tier\n\n## BYOK (Bring Your Own Keys)\n\nWhen users provide their own API keys, the CLI's local LLM proxy (`apps/cli/src/llm-proxy/`) routes LLM requests directly to the provider instead of through the Factory backend. Keys are stored in the user's OS keychain and never sent to Factory servers.\n\n## Dependency scanning\n\n`.github/workflows/endor-labs.yml` runs Endor Labs dependency scanning to detect known vulnerabilities in npm packages.\n\n## Rate limiting\n\nAPI rate limiting is applied at the backend level. `ResponseError429RateLimitExceeded` from `@factory/logging/errors` is the standard class for rate limit responses.\n",
