            "content": "# Patterns and conventions\n\n## Error handling\n\nThe codebase has a single source of truth for error handling: [`docs/error-handling.md`](../../docs/error-handling.md). Key points:\n\n**Never throw vanilla `Error`.** Use `MetaError` for internal errors and `ResponseErrorXxx` classes for API responses:\n\n```ts\nimport { MetaError, ResponseError404NotFound } from '@factory/logging/errors';\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n\n// Internal error\nthrow new MetaError('Session not found', { sessionId });\n\n// API route error\nthrow new ResponseError404NotFound('Session not found', { sessionId });\n```\n\n**Bubble errors by default.** Only catch errors when you have a concrete reason — a fallback value, a translation to a different error type, or when you want to handle and log locally.\n\n**One or the other.** If you call `logException()`, the error is handled locally (no rethrow). Otherwise, do not log — add breadcrumbs via `logInfo`/`logWarn` and rethrow.\n\n## State management (frontend)\n\nRedux Toolkit with entity adapters. Select state precisely, not generally:\n\n```ts\n// Wrong - triggers re-render on any state change\nconst { messageTree } = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.assembly);\n\n// Correct - only re-renders when this field changes\nconst messageTree = useSelector(\n  (state: RootState) => state.assembly.messageTree\n);\n```\n\nFor multiple fields, use multiple `useSelector` calls rather than destructuring a single slice.\n\n## UI components\n\nAll UI must use `@factory/core-ui` primitives. Never use raw HTML elements directly:\n\n| HTML element | Use instead |\n|---|---|\n| `<div>` | `<Box>` |\n| `<button>` | `<Button>` |\n| `<input>` | `<Input>` |\n| `<p>`, `<span>` | `<Text>` |\n| `<h1>`–`<h6>` | `<Header>` |\n\nColor tokens live in `packages/core-ui/src/colors/`. Always use `colors.semantics.*` tokens — never hardcode hex values.\n\n## Component structure\n\n- Maximum 200–300 lines per component\n- Extract long JSX blocks into named subcomponents\n- Pull repeated hooks/effects into custom hooks\n- Utility functions go in `utils/` files, not inline in components\n\n## File organisation (ESLint-enforced)\n\nESLint (`packages/eslint-config/`) enforces:\n- Enums in `enums.ts`, types in `types.ts`\n- API types in `packages/common/src/api/{service}/types.ts`\n- Absolute imports (`@factory/...`, `@/...`) — no relative imports beyond one level\n- No `require()` — use ES6 `import`\n\n## Feature flags\n\nFeature flags use Statsig. Define new flags in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` and create the corresponding gate in the Statsig console. See [`docs/feature-flags.md`](../../docs/feature-flags.md) for the full workflow.\n\nReact components use `useFeatureFlagValue(FactoryFeatureFlags.MyFlag)`. Backend routes use `getFeatureFlagInstance()`.\n\n## Logging\n\nUse `@factory/logging` everywhere. Three levels:\n\n```ts\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n\nlogInfo('Session started', { sessionId });\nlogWarn('LLM rate limit approaching', { usage: 950, limit: 1000 });\nlogException(error, 'Failed to load session', { sessionId });\n```\n\nNever call `logError` (it doesn't exist). The logging package automatically scrubs secrets from metadata.\n\n## Environment variables\n\nEnvironment variables use the `@factory/environment` package. Never read `process.env` directly in application code — this is enforced by the `no-direct-process-env` ESLint rule. See `packages/environment/` for the typed environment abstraction.\n\n## TypeScript\n\n- No `as` type assertions — use type-safe alternatives\n- No `any` — the ESLint config flags these\n- Prefer `interface` for object shapes that might be extended; `type` for unions, intersections, and utility types\n",
