            "content": "# Third-party integrations\n\nActive contributors: jerry, octavian, abhay\n\n## Purpose\n\nFactory integrates with external developer tools so the Droid agent can read context from, and write results to, the tools engineers already use. Integrations enable the agent to understand issues, pull requests, alerts, and project state without requiring copy-paste.\n\n## Supported integrations\n\n| Service | Category | What the agent can do |\n|---|---|---|\n| GitHub | Source control | Read PRs, issues, repo structure, create PRs, post comments |\n| Linear | Project management | Read/update issues, link sessions to tickets, create issues |\n| Slack | Communication | Post messages, read thread context |\n| Sentry | Error monitoring | Read error details and stack traces |\n| PagerDuty | Incident management | Read incidents and alerts |\n| Notion | Documentation | Read pages and databases |\n| Jira | Project management | Read issues and boards |\n| Figma | Design | Read design tokens and components |\n\n## Integration configuration\n\nUsers connect integrations through the Factory web app settings. Each integration stores OAuth tokens or API keys encrypted in Firestore via the backend.\n\nBackend integration services: `apps/backend/src/services/integrations/` (26 subdirectories covering each supported service).\n\nFrontend integration settings: `packages/common/src/integrations/` (types) and `packages/frontend/src/features/settings/`.\n\n## How integrations work in the agent\n\nWhen the agent needs context from an integration, it calls tools defined in `@factory/droid-core/src/tools/`. Each integration tool:\n1. Checks if the user has the integration configured\n2. Makes an authenticated request to the service API\n3. Formats the response for the LLM context\n\nThe CLI includes integration-specific tool definitions that extend the base tools in droid-core.\n\n## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n\nBeyond first-party integrations, users can connect external 