            "content": "# MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n\nActive contributors: shashank, arman\n\n## Purpose\n\nMCP (Model Context Protocol) is an open standard for exposing tools and resources to AI models. Factory supports MCP as a way to extend the Droid agent with external tool providers — any MCP-compatible server can make its tools available inside a Droid session.\n\n## How MCP works in Factory\n\nThe CLI includes an MCP client that connects to MCP servers at session startup. Configured MCP servers are loaded from the user's settings (`.factory/settings.json`). Each server exposes a list of tools that the agent can call alongside Factory's built-in tools.\n\n```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    CLI[\"Droid CLI\\n(MCP client)\"] -- \"stdio / HTTP\" --> S1[\"MCP server\\n(e.g., filesystem)\"]\n    CLI -- \"stdio / HTTP\" --> S2[\"MCP server\\n(e.g., custom tools)\"]\n    S1 --> T1[\"Tool: read_file\\nTool: search\"]\n    S2 --> T2[\"Custom tools\"]\n```\n\n## Configuration\n\nMCP servers are configured via the `droid mcp` subcommands:\n\n```bash\ndroid mcp add       # Add an MCP server\ndroid mcp list      # List configured servers\ndroid mcp remove    # Remove a server\n```\n\nConfiguration is stored in `packages/mcp/` (shared package) and user settings.\n\n## Factory Bridge MCP\n\n`apps/bridge-cli-mcp-server/` and `apps/bridge/` implement a Factory-specific MCP bridge — a way for external clients (e.g., Claude Desktop, Cursor, VS Code with MCP support) to connect to Factory's capabilities as an MCP server.\n\nThis is the reverse of the above: instead of Droid consuming MCP servers, Droid _exposes_ itself as an MCP server for other tools.\n\n## Key source files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `apps/cli/src/mcp/` | MCP client implementation |\n| `apps/cli/src/commands/mcp/` | MCP management commands |\n| `packages/mcp/` | Shared MCP types and utilities |\n| `apps/bridge/` | Factory as an MCP server (bridge) |\n| `apps/bridge-cli-mcp-server/` | CLI MCP server bridge |\n",
