            "content": "# Releases\n\n## Release cadence\n\nFactory runs automated daily releases on weekdays. The schedule is driven by `release-bump-version.yml`, which fires at 11 AM PST (19:00 UTC) Monday–Friday via a cron trigger. It creates a version bump PR against `dev`, and once that PR merges, `release-cut.yml` cuts a release branch and opens a PR from that branch into `dev`.\n\nHotfixes follow a separate path: a `hotfix` release type cherry-picks a specific PR number onto `main` rather than doing a full minor bump.\n\n### Branches\n\n| Branch | Meaning |\n|--------|---------|\n| `dev` | Integration branch; daily releases originate here |\n| `main` | Production-stable; hotfixes land here |\n| `release/*` | Short-lived branch created by `release-cut.yml` |\n\n## CLI release\n\n**Workflow:** `.github/workflows/cli-release.yml`  \n**npm package:** `cli-release-npm.yml`\n\nThe CLI is built as a Single Executable Application (SEA) using Node.js's built-in SEA feature — no runtime needed on the user's machine. Binaries are produced for macOS arm64, macOS x64, Linux x64, Linux arm64, and Windows x64.\n\nTriggers:\n- Push to `dev` → deploys to **development** and **staging** environments\n- Push to `main` → deploys to **production**\n- PR targeting `main` → deploys to **preprod**\n- Manual `workflow_dispatch` → choose environment explicitly\n\nThe workflow first runs `check-affected` to skip the release entirely when `@factory/cli` is unchanged.\n\nThe binary is named `droid` (production) or `droid-dev` / `droid-localhost` (local dev wrappers created by `cd apps/cli && npm run setup`).\n\n## Daemon release\n\n**Workflow:** `.github/workflows/factoryd-release.yml`\n\nThe daemon (`factoryd`) follows the same trigger logic as the CLI (dev → development+staging, main → production, PR to main → preprod). The `check-affected` step gates on `@factory/daemon`.\n\n`factoryd` is distributed as a standalone executable to:\n- The Factory Electron app (bundled at build time)\n- CDE sandboxes (downloaded from `downloads.factory.ai` on workspace initialization)\n\nThe daemon has a built-in auto-update mechanism that checks for new versions on startup.\n\n## Desktop release\n\n**Workflow:** `.github/workflows/desktop-release.yml`\n\nThe Electron app is built for macOS arm64, macOS x64, Linux x64, and optionally Windows x64. Windows builds are disabled by default because they require code-signing certificates; enable them with the `enable_windows` workflow input.\n\nTriggers are the same as the CLI and daemon (dev, main, PR to main). The built artifacts are uploaded to S3 and the app uses its auto-updater to pull new versions from there.\n\n## Web and backend release\n\n**Workflows:** `deploy-dev-web.yml`, `deploy-prod-app.yml`, `deploy-prod-admin.yml`, `deploy-prod.yml`\n\nWeb and backend are deployed to Vercel. `deploy-dev-web.yml` runs on every PR (preview deployment) and on push to `dev` (promotion to the `dev` Vercel environment). The production Vercel deploy is triggered as part of the coordinated `deploy-prod.yml` workflow that also handles Firebase Functions.\n\n## Version bumping\n\n**Workflow:** `.github/workflows/release-bump-version.yml`\n\nThe version bump workflow supports:\n- `major`, `minor`, `patch` bump types, or an exact version string\n- `release` type (merges into dev, then triggers `release-cut.yml`)\n- `hotfix` type (cherry-picks a specific PR number onto `main`, then triggers `hotfix-cut.yml`)\n\nVersion numbers live in `apps/cli/package.json`, `apps/daemon/package.json`, and `apps/desktop/package.json`. The `release-cut.yml` workflow reads them to label the release branch (e.g., `release/1.42.0`).\n\n## JetBrains and VSCode extensions\n\nThe JetBrains plugin and VSCode extension have their own release workflows (`jetbrains-plugin-release.yml`, `vscode-extension-release.yml`) that are independent of the main CLI/daemon release cycle.\n",
