            "content": "# Alerting\n\n## Sentry — application errors\n\nSentry is the primary alert source for code-level errors. The CLI, daemon, and backend all initialise a Sentry adapter at startup.\n\nSentry is enabled when any of these environment variables is truthy:\n\n- `VITE_VERCEL_ENV` (web app, desktop)\n- `ENABLE_SENTRY`\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_ENABLE_SENTRY` (backend)\n- `FACTORY_ENABLE_SENTRY` (daemon, CLI)\n\nThe adapter integration lives in `packages/logging/src/sentry/`. Each app sets up the adapter with its own Sentry DSN at startup; the rest of the codebase calls `logException` which routes to Sentry transparently.\n\n### Sentry 0 policy\n\nThe team targets zero unresolved Sentry issues. When `logException` is called, an issue is created if it has not been seen before. The goal is to either fix the root cause or mark issues as expected (with an explanation) rather than let them pile up.\n\n### What lands in Sentry\n\n- Every `logException` call (these swallow the error — see `docs/error-handling.md`)\n- Unhandled promise rejections and uncaught exceptions at the app boundary\n- `MetaError` instances thrown through the backend middleware\n\n### What does NOT land in Sentry\n\n- `logWarn` — warning only, no Sentry capture\n- `logInfo` — informational, no Sentry capture\n- `ResponseError4xx` classes thrown through the backend middleware (these are user errors, not application bugs)\n\n## Datadog — infrastructure metrics\n\nDatadog monitors system-level and infrastructure metrics:\n\n- Lambda invocation counts and error rates for the relay (`@factory/relay`)\n- Request counts and latency for the backend on Vercel\n- Custom application metrics forwarded from Axiom\n\nMonitors and SLOs are managed in the Datadog console. The Factory codebase does not contain Datadog monitor definitions in code; they are configured through the UI.\n\n## GitHub Actions CI failures\n\nGitHub Actions sends failure notifications via Slack. The `signal-deploy.yml` workflow posts deployment status to the team Slack channel. PR checks that fail block merges by branch protection rules on `dev` and `main`.\n\nTo see recent CI status for a branch:\n\n```bash\ngh run list --branch <branch-name>\ngh run view <run-id>\n```\n\n## Investigating an alert\n\n### Sentry issue\n\n1. Open the issue in Sentry and read the stack trace and breadcrumbs.\n2. Cross-reference with logs: search `~/.factory/logs/factoryd.log` or Axiom for the session ID or timestamp in the Sentry event.\n3. Identify whether the error is a regression (recently introduced) or pre-existing.\n4. Fix or mark as expected with a note.\n\n### Datadog alert\n\n1. Open the triggered monitor and look at the metric graph around the alert time.\n2. Correlate with deployment history: check if a release happened around that time (`gh release list`).\n3. Check Axiom for related log entries from the backend or daemon.\n\n### CI failure\n\n1. Open the failed run: `gh run view <run-id> --log-failed`.\n2. Determine if it is a flaky test (retry and observe) or a real regression.\n3. If a real regression, revert the offending PR or push a fix to the same branch.\n",
