            "content": "# Design decisions\n\n## Daemon architecture\n\nThe daemon (`factoryd`, in `apps/daemon/`) is an independent background process that sits between the user-facing UI and the individual droid processes. The communication stack is:\n\n```\nFrontend (DaemonSessionController.ts)\n    ↓ WebSocket JSON-RPC\nDaemon (droid-request-handler.ts)\n    ↓ stdin/stdout JSON-RPC\nCLI (streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.tsx)\n```\n\nKeeping the daemon separate from the UI means a running agent session survives UI restarts and disconnects. Multiple frontends (web app, desktop, IDE extensions) can connect to the same daemon simultaneously. The daemon also runs inside remote CDE sandboxes (E2B), where there is no local UI at all — the frontend connects over the network.\n\nThis design also means session state is never stored inside the UI process. The UI is a view layer; the daemon is the coordinator.\n\n## Bun for CLI and daemon\n\nBoth `apps/cli` and `apps/daemon` run on Bun rather than Node.js. The main reason was startup time: Bun launches significantly faster than Node.js, which matters for a CLI that users run many times per day. Bun also runs TypeScript natively without a compilation step during development, which simplifies the local dev loop (`droid-dev` runs directly from source).\n\nThe build output is still compiled to a Node.js-compatible SEA binary (see below) so users don't need Bun installed. Bun is only required for contributors working on the CLI or daemon.\n\n## JSON-RPC 2.0 for the WebSocket protocol\n\nThe WebSocket protocol between the frontend and daemon uses JSON-RPC 2.0. This was chosen because:\n\n- It is a simple, well-specified standard with request/response and notification semantics\n- Multiple clients can connect to the same WebSocket server and receive the same notifications\n- The protocol is bidirectional: the daemon can push events (session notifications, terminal output, permission requests) without the client polling\n- Tooling and debuggers exist for it\n\nThe message schemas are defined in `packages/common/src/droid/schemas/cli.ts` and the notification types in `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n## Turborepo\n\nThe repo uses Turborepo for orchestrating build, test, lint, and typecheck tasks across all packages and apps. Turborepo understands the dependency graph between packages and caches task outputs on disk (and optionally in a remote cache). This means `npm run build` only rebuilds packages whose inputs have changed since the last run.\n\nThe task dependency graph is declared in `turbo.json`. The main practical impact for day-to-day work is the `--filter` syntax (see [Pitfalls](./pitfalls.md)) and the fact that you must pass `--` before `--filter` when using npm scripts.\n\n## SEA binaries (Single Executable Applications)\n\nThe CLI and daemon are distributed as Node.js SEA binaries. A SEA bundles the entire JavaScript bundle (produced by Bun's bundler) into a single native executable — no Node.js or Bun runtime needs to be installed on the user's machine.\n\nThis matters for distribution: `droid` is installed via npm (`npm install -g factory-cli`) or downloaded from `downloads.factory.ai`, and it just works on any supported OS/architecture. The supported targets are macOS arm64, macOS x64, Linux x64, Linux arm64, and Windows x64.\n\nBuild scripts for each target are in `apps/cli/package.json` and `apps/daemon/package.json` (e.g., `npm run build:sea:mac:arm64`). In CI, the release workflows build all targets in parallel on appropriate runners.\n",
