            "content": "# Pitfalls and danger zones\n\nCommon mistakes that cost time or break things silently.\n\n## `npm run dev` at the root is disabled\n\nRunning `npm run dev` from the monorepo root does nothing useful — it is intentionally disabled. Use the named scripts instead:\n\n```bash\nnpm run dev:web      # backend + web + storybook + admin + daemon (works over SSH)\nnpm run dev:desktop  # backend + web + storybook + admin + desktop (local only)\n```\n\nFor CLI development, run `droid-dev` or `droid-localhost` separately after `cd apps/cli && npm run setup`.\n\n## Turbo filter syntax: always use `--` before `--filter`\n\nnpm eats `--filter` if you don't separate it:\n\n```bash\n# WRONG — npm consumes --filter; turbo runs every package (uses ~9 GB RAM)\nnpm run test --filter=@factory/frontend\n\n# CORRECT — -- passes --filter through to turbo\nnpm run test -- --filter=@factory/frontend\nnpm run test -- --filter=@factory/common --filter=@factory/daemon-core\n```\n\nThis applies to all turbo-based scripts: `test`, `typecheck`, `lint`, `fix`, `build`.\n\n## CLI changes require three steps\n\nAfter changing code in `apps/cli` or any package it depends on:\n\n1. **Rebuild:** `cd apps/cli && npm run setup`\n2. **Restart the daemon:** kill the running `factoryd` process and start a new one\n3. **Start a new session:** old sessions will not pick up the rebuilt binary\n\nSkipping any of these steps means you are still running old code. The `droid-dev` wrapper runs from TypeScript source via Bun, so it does not need a rebuild step — but you still need to restart the daemon and start a new session.\n\n## Never use raw HTML elements in UI code\n\n`apps/web`, `apps/desktop`, and `packages/frontend` must use `@factory/core-ui` primitives. Raw `<div>`, `<button>`, `<input>`, and `<span>` are forbidden. ESLint enforces this.\n\n```typescript\n// WRONG\n<div className=\"container\"><button onClick={…}>Save</button></div>\n\n// CORRECT\nimport { Box, Button } from '@factory/core-ui';\n<Box><Button onClick={…}>Save</Button></Box>\n```\n\nDo not create custom UI primitives — if the component you need does not exist in `@factory/core-ui`, add it there first.\n\n## Never throw vanilla `Error`\n\nAll thrown errors must carry metadata. Use `MetaError` for internal bugs and the `ResponseErrorXXX` classes for HTTP errors:\n\n```typescript\n// WRONG\nthrow new Error('Something broke');\n\n// CORRECT\nimport { MetaError } from '@factory/logging/errors';\nthrow new MetaError('Something broke', { context, userId });\n```\n\nThe `ResponseError` classes map to specific HTTP status codes. Using the right one means the backend middleware returns the correct status instead of a generic 500. See `docs/error-handling.md` for the full table.\n\n## Never read `process.env` directly\n\nUse the `@factory/environment` package instead. Direct `process.env` access is banned by the `no-direct-process-env` ESLint rule. The environment package provides typed accessors and centralises the environment variable definitions.\n\n```typescript\n// WRONG\nconst apiUrl = process.env.FACTORY_API_BASE_URL;\n\n// CORRECT\nimport { getEnvironment } from '@factory/environment';\nconst { apiBaseUrl } = getEnvironment();\n```\n\n## Use absolute imports, not relative cross-package imports\n\nESLint enforces absolute imports using the workspace aliases (`@factory/…`, `@/…`). Importing across packages with relative paths (e.g., `../../packages/frontend/src/…`) breaks the module boundary, confuses bundlers, and is not allowed.\n\n```typescript\n// WRONG\nimport { something } from '../../../packages/frontend/src/utils';\n\n// CORRECT\nimport { something } from '@factory/frontend/utils';\n```\n\n## `logException` and rethrow is a bug\n\nCalling `logException` and then rethrowing creates a duplicate Sentry issue. Pick one:\n\n```typescript\n// Swallow the error (use logException, do NOT rethrow)\ntry {\n  doThing();\n} catch (error) {\n  logException(error, 'doThing failed', { context });\n  return fallback;\n}\n\n// Propagate the error (use logWarn for breadcrumbs, rethrow the ORIGINAL error)\ntry {\n  doThing();\n} catch (error) {\n  logWarn('doThing failed', { context });\n  throw error; // original stack preserved\n}\n```\n\nSee `docs/error-handling.md` for the full error handling guide.\n",
