            "content": "# Glossary\n\nTerms used throughout the Factory codebase and documentation.\n\n## Core concepts\n\n**Droid** — The AI agent that executes software engineering tasks. The word is used for both the product (Factory Droid) and the runtime executable (`droid` binary, `apps/cli`).\n\n**Session** — A single conversation between a user and the Droid agent. Sessions persist in Firestore and can be resumed. Each session has its own message history and tool execution log.\n\n**factoryd** — The Factory daemon binary (`apps/daemon`). A background process that manages droid sessions and terminal access. Named `factoryd` following the Unix daemon naming convention.\n\n**TUI** — Terminal User Interface. The full-screen Ink/React interface rendered by the CLI when started without arguments. Provides a chat window, tool confirmation dialogs, and status indicators.\n\n**Exec mode** — Headless (non-interactive) execution mode. Invoked via `droid exec` or by calling the CLI with the `exec` subcommand. Produces structured output suitable for CI pipelines.\n\n**Mission** — A large autonomous task decomposed by an orchestrator agent into discrete features, each executed by a separate worker session. Also called AGI mode. See [missions feature](../features/missions.md).\n\n**Worker session** — A droid session spawned by a mission orchestrator to implement a single feature. Workers run autonomously and report back to the orchestrator.\n\n**Orchestrator** — The top-level agent in a mission run that decomposes the goal, spawns workers, and monitors overall progress.\n\n## Protocol\n\n**JSON-RPC 2.0** — The protocol used for all inter-process communication: frontend↔daemon (over WebSocket) and daemon↔CLI (over stdin/stdout).\n\n**DroidServerMethod** — JSON-RPC method names sent from the frontend/daemon to the CLI (e.g., `droid.initialize_session`, `droid.add_user_message`). Defined in `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n**DroidClientMethod** — JSON-RPC method names sent from the CLI back to the frontend/daemon (e.g., `droid.session_notification`, `droid.request_permission`). Defined in `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n**SessionNotificationType** — The sub-type of a `droid.session_notification` notification (e.g., `tool_result`, `create_message`, `droid_working_state_changed`). Defined in `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n**DroidWorkingState** — The current activity of the agent: `idle`, `streaming_assistant_message`, `waiting_for_tool_confirmation`, `executing_tool`, or `compacting_conversation`.\n\n## Tools and permissions\n\n**Tool confirmation** — Before executing a risky tool (file edit, shell command), the CLI sends a `droid.request_permission` request to the frontend. The user approves or denies the action.\n\n**ToolConfirmationOutcome** — The result of a permission request: `proceed_once`, `proceed_always`, `proceed_auto_run`, `proceed_edit`, or `cancel`. Defined in `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n**Autonomy mode** — A setting controlling how aggressively the agent confirms actions. Modes range from full confirmation on every action to fully autonomous with no prompts.\n\n**ACP (Agent Command Protocol)** — An internal protocol used for communication when the CLI is running as a child process of the daemon (not over stdin/stdout but via a dedicated IPC channel). Located in `apps/cli/src/acp/` and `apps/daemon/src/acp/`.\n\n## Infrastructure\n\n**CDE (Cloud Development Environment)** — A remote ephemeral development environment (powered by E2B sandboxes) where the daemon and CLI can run. The desktop app connects to CDEs the same way it connects to a local daemon.\n\n**E2B** — The cloud sandbox provider used for remote CDEs. The backend service is at `apps/backend/src/services/e2b/`.\n\n**Firestore** — Google Cloud Firestore used as the primary database for sessions, organizations, users, and settings.\n\n**WorkOS** — The authentication provider. Handles sign-in, user management, and organization management. The backend uses the `@workos-inc/node` SDK.\n\n**Orb** — The billing platform used for usage-based pricing. The backend service is at `apps/backend/src/services/orb/`.\n\n**Statsig** — The feature flag platform. Flags are defined in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` and evaluated via the Statsig SDK.\n\n## Packages and architecture\n\n**@factory/core-ui** — The mandatory design system package. All web UI components must use its primitives (`Box`, `Flex`, `Button`, `Input`, etc.) rather than raw HTML elements.\n\n**@factory/droid-core** — The core AI agent library. Provides tool definitions, LLM provider adapters, message formatting, and streaming utilities.\n\n**@factory/common** — The shared types, enums, and API contracts used by all packages. The single source of truth for cross-boundary data shapes.\n\n**@factory/daemon-core** — The reusable daemon logic that both `apps/daemon` and `apps/cli` (when running in daemon mode) depend on.\n\n**@factory/frontend** — Shared React features used by both `apps/web` and `apps/desktop`.\n\n**MetaError** — The base error class used for internal errors. All code must throw `MetaError` (or a `ResponseErrorXXX` subclass) instead of the built-in `Error`. Defined in `packages/logging/src/errors/`.\n\n**Compaction** — The process of summarizing an overly long conversation to reduce token count. The CLI requests user confirmation before compacting.\n\n**Skills** — Reusable prompt-and-instruction bundles stored in `.factory/skills/` or `~/.factory/skills/`. The CLI activates them on demand to give the agent specialized capabilities.\n\n**MCP (Model Context Protocol)** — A protocol for connecting external tool servers to the agent. The CLI can connect to MCP servers over stdio or HTTP, adding their tools to the agent's toolset.\n",
