            "content": "# Testing\n\n## Test frameworks\n\n| Package / App | Framework | Runner |\n|---|---|---|\n| `apps/backend` | Jest | `npx jest` |\n| `apps/cli` | Jest + `@microsoft/tui-test` | `npx jest` / `tui-test` |\n| `packages/frontend` | Vitest | `npx vitest` |\n| `packages/droid-core` | Jest | `npx jest` |\n| `packages/daemon-core` | Jest | `npx jest` |\n| Most other packages | Jest | `npx jest` |\n\n## Running tests\n\n```bash\n# All tests (requires ~9 GB RAM)\nnpm run test\n\n# Targeted — always use -- before --filter\nnpm run test -- --filter=apps/backend\nnpm run test -- --filter=@factory/droid-core --filter=@factory/common\n\n# Single file\ncd apps/backend && npx jest src/services/billing/billingService.test.ts\ncd packages/frontend && npx vitest run src/features/sessions/index.test.ts\n```\n\n## Frontend tests require jsdom\n\nAny test that uses browser APIs (`document`, `window`, React hooks, DOM elements) must declare the jsdom environment at the top of the file:\n\n```typescript\n/**\n * @jest-environment jsdom\n */\n```\n\nWithout this pragma, tests that touch `document` throw `ReferenceError: document is not defined`.\n\n## What \"unit tests\" means here\n\nUnit tests are 1:1 with a single source file. A test for `service.ts` only validates logic inside `service.ts`. It does not test the modules that `service.ts` calls — those get their own tests.\n\nWhen `service.ts` calls heavy external dependencies (Firestore, external APIs, the filesystem), mock those calls. When it calls pure internal utilities, leave those real.\n\n## Mocking patterns\n\n### Top-level mock with `requireActual`\n\n```typescript\njest.mock('@factory/logging', () => ({\n  ...jest.requireActual('@factory/logging'),\n  logInfo: jest.fn(),\n  logException: jest.fn(),\n}));\n\nbeforeEach(() => jest.resetAllMocks());\n```\n\n### Singleton isolation\n\nFor modules that export singletons, reset the module cache between tests rather than calling reset functions:\n\n```typescript\nbeforeEach(() => jest.resetModules());\n\nit('test', async () => {\n  const { getService } = await import('./service');\n  // fresh singleton\n});\n```\n\n### Mock return values\n\n```typescript\n(mockFunction as jest.Mock).mockResolvedValue({ data: 'value' });\n(mockFunction as jest.Mock).mockImplementation((arg) => arg * 2);\n```\n\n## E2E tests\n\n### CLI E2E tests (`apps/cli/e2e-tests/`)\n\nCLI E2E tests use `@microsoft/tui-test` to drive the full TUI in a real terminal emulator. These tests live in `apps/cli/e2e-tests/`. They are run separately from unit tests:\n\n```bash\ncd apps/cli && npm run test:e2e\n```\n\nThe `tui-test.config.ts` file configures the terminal dimensions, snapshot behavior, and test timeouts.\n\n### Playwright E2E tests (`apps/web/e2e/`)\n\nBrowser E2E tests for the web app use Playwright. From the repo root:\n\n```bash\ncd packages/frontend && npm run test:e2e\n```\n\nFor a visual run with the browser visible:\n\n```bash\ncd packages/frontend && npm run test:e2e -- --headed --debug\n```\n\nSee `docs/playwright-e2e-testing.md` for fixtures, helpers, and CI configuration.\n\n## Coverage\n\nTests are collected under `coverage/` in each package. There is no enforced global coverage threshold, but new code for critical paths (session management, billing, auth) should have meaningful coverage.\n\n## Testing hooks in React\n\nReact hook tests need the jsdom environment and use `@testing-library/react`:\n\n```typescript\n/**\n * @jest-environment jsdom\n */\nimport { renderHook, act } from '@testing-library/react';\n\nit('increments count', () => {\n  const { result } = renderHook(() => useCounter());\n  act(() => result.current.increment());\n  expect(result.current.count).toBe(1);\n});\n```\n\nSee `docs/testing-react-hooks.md` for advanced patterns including async hooks, context providers, and Redux store wrappers.\n",
