            "content": "# Session management\n\nThe daemon manages the lifecycle of droid sessions — from spawning a fresh CLI process to routing messages and handling session termination.\n\n## Session lifecycle\n\n```mermaid\nstateDiagram-v2\n    [*] --> Initializing: daemon.initialize_session\n    Initializing --> Active: CLI process started\n    Active --> Active: add_user_message / tool execution\n    Active --> Interrupting: daemon.interrupt_session\n    Interrupting --> Active: interrupt complete\n    Active --> [*]: session closed or process exits\n```\n\n## Initializing a session\n\nWhen the frontend sends `daemon.initialize_session`, the daemon:\n\n1. Validates the session parameters (auth, model, settings)\n2. Spawns a new `droid` CLI process as a child process with stdin/stdout piped\n3. Establishes a JSON-RPC 2.0 channel over stdin/stdout\n4. Registers the session in its in-memory session map\n5. Sends the initial context (session ID, settings, user info) to the CLI over stdin\n\nThe CLI process starts, initializes its own state, and sends back a confirmation notification.\n\n## Message routing\n\nAfter initialization, messages flow in both directions:\n\n**Frontend → CLI:**\n- Frontend sends `daemon.add_user_message` with the user's text\n- Daemon writes the JSON-RPC message to the CLI process's stdin\n- CLI receives it, processes it (LLM call, tools), and sends back notifications\n\n**CLI → Frontend:**\n- CLI sends `droid.session_notification` or `droid.request_permission` over stdout\n- Daemon reads from the CLI process's stdout\n- Daemon forwards the notification to the correct WebSocket connection\n\n## Tool confirmation flow\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant CLI as apps/cli\n    participant Daemon as apps/daemon\n    participant Frontend\n\n    CLI->>Daemon: droid.request_permission (over stdout)\n    Daemon->>Frontend: droid.request_permission (over WebSocket)\n    Frontend->>Frontend: User approves/denies\n    Frontend->>Daemon: response (proceed_once / cancel)\n    Daemon->>CLI: response (over stdin)\n    CLI->>CLI: executes or skips tool\n```\n\nThe permission request is a JSON-RPC request (with an `id`), and the daemon correlates the response by `id` when forwarding it back to the CLI.\n\n## Session interruption\n\n`daemon.interrupt_session` sends a SIGINT-equivalent signal to the CLI process. The CLI catches this, stops the current tool execution, and returns control to the agent loop (which typically exits or waits for the next message).\n\n## Worker sessions (missions)\n\nIn mission mode, the daemon manages multiple CLI processes simultaneously — one orchestrator and multiple worker sessions. Worker sessions are spawned, monitored, and killed via:\n\n- `daemon.initialize_session` with a `DecompSessionType.Worker` flag\n- `daemon.kill_worker_session` to terminate specific workers\n\nThe orchestrator CLI coordinates workers through the daemon, sending mission-specific notifications (`MISSION_WORKER_STARTED`, `MISSION_WORKER_COMPLETED`, etc.) that the frontend renders in the mission control panel.\n\n## In-memory state\n\nThe daemon holds session state in memory only — it does not persist session data. Persistent data (messages, metadata) is stored in Firestore via the backend API, called by the CLI. If the daemon restarts, active sessions need to be re-initialized.\n\n## Key source files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `packages/daemon-core/src/droid/` | Droid process lifecycle management |\n| `packages/daemon-core/src/server/handlers/` | JSON-RPC request handlers per method |\n| `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts` | Method names and notification types |\n| `packages/common/src/droid/schemas/` | JSON schema validation for protocol messages |\n",
