            "content": "# MCP integration\n\nModel Context Protocol (MCP) is an open standard for connecting external tool servers to AI agents. The Droid CLI supports MCP servers, making it possible to extend the agent's capabilities with custom tools from any MCP-compatible server.\n\n## How MCP works in Factory\n\nWhen the CLI starts a session, it connects to any configured and enabled MCP servers. Tools from those servers are loaded into the tool registry alongside the built-in tools. The LLM then has access to all tools — built-in and MCP — in the same way.\n\n## MCP server types\n\n| Transport | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `stdio` | Spawns a local process and communicates over stdin/stdout |\n| `http` | Connects to a remote HTTP server |\n\nDefined in `McpServerType` in `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts`.\n\n## Server status lifecycle\n\n| Status | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `connecting` | Establishing connection |\n| `connected` | Ready, tools loaded |\n| `disconnected` | Connection lost |\n| `failed` | Failed to connect |\n| `disabled` | User-disabled |\n\n## Managing MCP servers\n\n### Via CLI commands\n\n```bash\ndroid mcp add          # add a new MCP server\ndroid mcp remove       # remove a server\ndroid mcp list         # list configured servers\ndroid mcp toggle       # enable/disable a server\n```\n\nCLI MCP commands are in `apps/cli/src/commands/mcp/`.\n\n### Via daemon protocol\n\nThe frontend can manage MCP servers for a live session through daemon methods:\n\n- `daemon.add_mcp_server`\n- `daemon.remove_mcp_server`\n- `daemon.toggle_mcp_server`\n- `daemon.list_mcp_registry` — list servers from the MCP registry\n- `daemon.list_mcp_tools` — list tools from connected servers\n- `daemon.toggle_mcp_tool` — enable/disable individual tools\n\n### Authentication\n\nSome MCP servers require OAuth authentication. The flow:\n\n1. CLI sends `mcp_auth_required` notification to frontend\n2. User clicks \"Authenticate\" in the MCP settings panel\n3. Frontend sends `daemon.authenticate_mcp_server`\n4. CLI opens a browser for the OAuth flow\n5. After authentication, CLI sends `mcp_auth_completed`\n\n## Tool integration\n\nMCP tools appear in the tool registry with their server's prefix. When the LLM calls an MCP tool, the CLI dispatches the call to the appropriate server and returns the result like any other tool.\n\nMCP tools may also require confirmation depending on their risk level, following the same confirmation flow as built-in tools.\n\n## Configuration\n\nMCP servers are stored in the user's settings file (`~/.factory/settings.json`). The settings include:\n\n- Server name and type\n- Command/URL and arguments\n- Environment variables\n- Enabled/disabled state\n- Auth token (if authenticated)\n\n## Key source files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `apps/cli/src/mcp/` | MCP client management, server lifecycle |\n| `apps/cli/src/commands/mcp/` | MCP CLI commands |\n| `apps/cli/src/components/McpManager.tsx` | TUI MCP management panel |\n| `apps/cli/src/exec/mcpStatusHandler.ts` | MCP status tracking during exec |\n| `packages/common/src/droid/enums.ts` | `McpServerType`, `McpServerStatus`, `McpStatus` |\n",
