            "content": "# Lore\n\nThe history of this codebase is the history of a platform that kept reinventing its own foundation while keeping the product running. What started as a single Next.js app has, in under 18 months, become a 12-app monorepo with a terminal agent, a desktop app, a daemon, a relay service, and a signal processor — most of which didn't exist a year ago.\n\n---\n\n## Eras\n\n### Era 1 — Bootstrap (Sep 2024 – Oct 2024)\n\nThe repository opened with a single commit on Sep 30, 2024: _\"Initial commit from Create Next App\"_. Within the first week, the basics were in place: styled-components, a color system, Inter font, and a Redux store. By early October a Firestore/Firebase backend was wired in, sessions and blueprints had their first UI scaffolding, and the first authentication flow was written.\n\nThis was a single Next.js application — no monorepo, no packages directory, no CLI. The entire product lived in one `src/` tree. Blueprints (reusable session templates) and Sessions (conversations with an AI) were the two core concepts. Code search via Zoekt was added in Oct 2024, one of the earliest integrations still present in some form today.\n\nKey events:\n- **Sep 2024** — Initial commit from Create Next App; Redux store, styled-components, Firebase auth wired in within the first two weeks\n- **Oct 2024** — Sessions and Blueprints UI scaffolded; Zoekt code search integration; first PR (#1) merged (Prettier setup)\n- **Oct 2024** — jotai added alongside Redux (early sign of future state-management churn)\n\n---\n\n### Era 2 — Assembly Platform (Nov 2024 – Jan 2025)\n\nThe app was being called \"Assembly\" by this point, living at the GitHub repo `Factory-AI/factory-assembly`. The pace accelerated sharply: the Oct 2024 commit count was 319, climbing to 427 in December.\n\nMulti-model support arrived in Nov 2024 when Claude was integrated via Anthropic alongside the existing OpenAI path. o1 streaming support came shortly after. LangSmith was added as an observability layer. Local repo indexing using embedding generation and a Weaviate vector database arrived in Nov 2024, enabling semantic code search. WorkOS was integrated for auth in Nov 2024.\n\nJanuary 2025 shipped release 1.3.0 — the first release in the `1.3.x` cadence that would continue for months.\n\nKey events:\n- **Nov 2024** — Claude (Anthropic) model added alongside OpenAI; o1 streaming support\n- **Nov 2024** — LangSmith integrated for LLM trace observability\n- **Nov 2024** — Local repo indexing launched using Weaviate vector DB + Voyage embedding generation\n- **Nov 2024** — WorkOS auth migrated in\n- **Dec 2024** — Prompt caching for Claude; Azure OpenAI client replaced by direct OpenAI\n- **Jan 2025** — Release 1.3.0 ships; `Droid Mode` feature flag scaffolded\n\n---\n\n### Era 3 — Droid Mode and MCP (Jan 2025 – Mar 2025)\n\nWith release 1.3.0, a new concept appeared in the commit log: \"Droid Mode.\" This was a gated agentic experience — a mode where the AI could take tool-calling actions against the codebase rather than just chat. Agentic Search tooling was built incrementally: Zoekt-backed file search, regex tools, file-contents retrieval.\n\nIn Feb 2025, MCP (Model Context Protocol) arrived. MCP tools could be called through the chat interface via a bridge connector, enabling the assembly platform to reach out to external tool servers. The bridge was also the beginning of the CDE (Cloud Development Environment) concept — connecting the web app to a remote code workspace.\n\nCommit volume stayed around 375–405/month through Q1 2025, steady but not yet the acceleration that came later.\n\nKey events:\n- **Jan 2025** — Droid Mode feature flag; agentic search scaffolding (Zoekt file tools, regex search)\n- **Feb 2025** — MCP integration shipped; Bridge connector established for CDE workspace connections\n- **Mar 2025** — PR volumes reached #2200+ range\n\n---\n\n### Era 4 — Package Extraction and Monorepo Formation (Apr 2025 – Jun 2025)\n\nApril 2025 was when the codebase became a genuine monorepo. Before this, there was one main Next.js app (`apps/factory-app`) with everything inside it. In April, the first shared packages were extracted: `packages/logging`, `packages/services`, `packages/eslint-config`, `packages/utils`, and `packages/models`. These were separated from the main app so that the upcoming CLI could share code without importing from a Next.js application.\n\nJune 2025 was particularly active. `packages/ui` was created as a home for foundational UI components extracted from factory-app. The Bridge connector was migrated into the monorepo as a proper app. Jest was replaced with Vitest in factory-app. Nx was briefly introduced as the build orchestrator and then reversed in favor of a simpler Turbo setup (the Turbo config was already present and the Nx migration appears to have been a short-lived experiment). LangSmith was removed. Clank — an early bridge/workspace client — was also deleted.\n\nKey events:\n- **Apr 2025** — packages/logging, packages/services, packages/eslint-config, packages/utils, packages/models extracted; packages/models first home for Firestore model definitions\n- **Jun 2025** — packages/ui (later core-ui) created; Bridge monorepo migration; Jest → Vitest migration in factory-app\n- **Jun 2025** — Nx build system briefly introduced and then replaced with simplified Turbo config (churn resolved by Jul 2025)\n- **Jun 2025** — LangSmith removed; Clank removed\n- **Jun 2025** — Migrations code moved into the monorepo from a separate repo\n\n---\n\n### Era 5 — The CLI Is Born (Jul 2025 – Sep 2025)\n\nThe most consequential architectural addition in the repo's history landed in Jul 2025: `apps/factory-cli` was initialized. This was the Droid terminal agent — a Bun-based CLI that would eventually replace the web-only Droid experience for developers. `packages/droid-core` was also extracted in July as the shared AI agent library.\n\nThe CLI grew quickly. By August 2025, it had Spec Mode — a planning-before-execution mode where the agent proposes a plan and waits for approval before writing code. September 2025 brought BYOK (Bring Your Own Key), letting users supply their own API keys for Anthropic and other providers.\n\nCommit velocity climbed with the CLI: 527/month in May, 637 in August, 741 in September — the highest sustained monthly rate in the project's history.\n\nKey events:\n- **Jul 2025** — `apps/factory-cli` initialized; `packages/droid-core` extracted as shared AI agent library\n- **Jul 2025** — Turbo monorepo setup simplified to direct TypeScript-only (no Nx)\n- **Aug 2025** — Spec Mode introduced in CLI (plan-first execution mode)\n- **Sep 2025** — BYOK (Bring Your Own Key) launched for Anthropic and other providers\n- **Sep 2025** — Commit count reaches 741/month — highest monthly peak\n\n---\n\n### Era 6 — Desktop, Daemon, and Assembly V3 (Oct 2025 – Dec 2025)\n\nOctober 2025 was another structural reset. Three new applications appeared simultaneously: `apps/web` (Assembly V3, a Vite+React rewrite of the frontend), `apps/desktop` (an Electron wrapper), and `apps/daemon` (the `factoryd` background service). The daemon's role was to own terminal capabilities and act as a local bridge between the CLI's JSON-RPC calls and the system.\n\nSeveral new packages appeared alongside: `packages/core-ui` (the mandatory design system, replacing the earlier packages/ui), `packages/frontend` (shared React features), `packages/droid-sdk` (a TypeScript client for the droid exec API). The audit logging system was tagged at `audit-logging-v1.0` in Oct 2025.\n\nNovember brought Electron auto-updates and the `packages/updater` package. The `apps/admin` app appeared in December 2025.\n\nKey events:\n- **Oct 2025** — `apps/web` (Assembly V3), `apps/desktop` (Electron), `apps/daemon` (factoryd) all initialized\n- **Oct 2025** — `packages/core-ui`, `packages/frontend`, `packages/droid-sdk` added; audit logging tagged v1.0 and v1.1\n- **Oct 2025** — factory-cli gains TUI e2e test infrastructure (`@microsoft/tui-test`)\n- **Nov 2025** — Electron auto-updates; `packages/updater` extracted\n- **Nov 2025** — Weaviate purge cron job removed from factory-app (end of Weaviate era)\n- **Dec 2025** — `apps/admin` appears; `packages/environment` added for typed config\n\n---\n\n### Era 7 — Missions, Renaming, and New Services (Jan 2026 – Present)\n\n2026 opened with housekeeping: `apps/factory-cli` was renamed to `apps/cli` in Jan 2026, and `apps/factory-app` was renamed to `apps/backend`. These renames formalized names that had been used informally for months.\n\nThe biggest new capability was Missions (internally codenamed \"Colossus\"): a multi-agent orchestration system where a planner agent decomposes a large task and spawns worker agents to execute parts in parallel. Colossus V0 was merged in Jan 2026 under the name \"projects,\" then promptly renamed to \"missions\" in the same month. The missions feature flag was deleted in Mar 2026 as it graduated to generally available.\n\nFebruary 2026 saw `apps/relay` (a WebSocket relay for BYO Computer scenarios) and `apps/signal` (ported from data-eng for ML signal processing) join the apps directory. `packages/runtime/auth` was also added as a dedicated auth abstraction. The `/wiki` command was launched in Feb 2026 — giving the CLI the ability to generate documentation for a repository and store it in Firestore.\n\nKey events:\n- **Jan 2026** — `apps/factory-cli` → `apps/cli`; `apps/factory-app` → `apps/backend`\n- **Jan 2026** — Colossus V0 (Missions) merged; \"project\" renamed to \"mission\" immediately after\n- **Feb 2026** — `apps/relay` (BYO Computer relay service) and `apps/signal` added\n- **Feb 2026** — `packages/runtime/auth` added; auth refactored across CLI, daemon, desktop\n- **Feb 2026** — `/wiki` command launched; full Firestore-backed wiki feature shipped\n- **Mar 2026** — E2B added as computer provider; Cloudflare and Sprites computer providers removed\n- **Mar 2026** — Missions feature flag deleted (feature graduates)\n- **Mar 2026** — CJK (Japanese, Chinese, Korean) full internationalization in CLI\n- **Mar 2026** — Git worktree native support (`--worktree` flag) added\n\n---\n\n## Longest-Standing Features\n\n**Sessions** — The session concept (a conversation with context) was in the first commit batch in Sep 2024. The data model has been refactored multiple times, but the core concept of a named session with messages and tool results is the oldest surviving abstraction in the codebase.\n\n**Blueprints** — Blueprint scaffolding appeared in Oct 2024. Blueprints (reusable session templates) are among the earliest features and appear to still exist, having outlasted several surrounding systems.\n\n**Firebase/Firestore integration** — Wired in Oct 2024 and remains the primary persistence layer 18 months later. The Firestore collection names and patterns introduced early on are still the backbone of the backend.\n\n**WorkOS auth** — Integrated in Nov 2024, WorkOS has been the authentication provider since the project's first weeks and has survived multiple architectural upheavals including the transition from a monolithic Next.js app to the current multi-app monorepo.\n\n**Zoekt code search** — Added in Oct 2024 as one of the first backend integrations. Zoekt-powered search surfaced in the Droid Mode agentic search tools in early 2025 and appears to remain part of the indexing infrastructure.\n\n**Redux** — Scaffolded in the first week (Sep 2024). Though jotai appeared alongside it by October 2024 and the newer apps (cli, desktop, web) do not use Redux, the original factory-app/backend still carries Redux state for some features.\n\n---\n\n## Deprecated Features\n\n**LangSmith** (Nov 2024 – Jul 2025): LangSmith was added in Nov 2024 to trace LLM calls through the LangChain observability platform. It was used to log conversation data, instrument compaction, and catch orphaned traces. It was progressively stripped down from May 2025 onward and fully purged in Jul 2025. No direct replacement was named; the project shifted toward Sentry and custom logging via `packages/logging`.\n\n**Weaviate vector database** (Nov 2024 – Nov 2025): Weaviate was introduced in Nov 2024 to store embeddings for local repo indexing — the semantic code search feature. Voyage AI was used for embedding generation. Weaviate-related code shrank through mid-2025 as retention was tightened, and the cron job that purged Weaviate was removed in Nov 2025. Local repo indexing appears to have been replaced or discontinued as the CLI-first approach moved index management elsewhere.\n\n**Clank** (unknown introduction – Jun 2025): Clank was removed in Jun 2025 with no fanfare. Based on surrounding context, it was likely an early Bridge/CDE client abstraction that was superseded by the Bridge monorepo migration and the proper daemon-based approach.\n\n**Assembly V2 UI** (early 2025 – Oct 2025): There are branch references (`nikita/factory-v2`, `nikita/factory-v2-6`) suggesting an incremental V2 redesign of the Assembly UI was in progress through early 2025. This was superseded by Assembly V3 (`apps/web`), a full Vite+React rebuild launched in Oct 2025 separate from the existing Next.js app.\n\n**Nx build orchestration** (Jun 2025 – Jul 2025): Nx was introduced as the build orchestrator in Jun 2025 (`chore(nx): complete Turbo → Nx migration`) and replaced again less than a month later with a simplified Turbo setup. This appears to have been a brief experiment.\n\n**Cloudflare and Sprites computer providers** (unknown – Mar 2026): Two computer execution backends — Cloudflare and Sprites — were removed in Mar 2026, replaced by E2B as the primary ephemeral compute provider.\n\n**Legacy OpenAI preview models** (various – Mar 2026): Several OpenAI preview model IDs were deprecated in Mar 2026 as production-stable replacements were promoted. This is an ongoing process as model generations rotate.\n\n---\n\n## Major Rewrites\n\n**Single monolith → monorepo package extraction (Apr – Jun 2025):** Before April 2025, all server code lived inside `apps/factory-app` (a Next.js app). No shared packages existed. Over April–June, `packages/logging`, `packages/services`, `packages/utils`, `packages/models`, and `packages/eslint-config` were all extracted. The motivation was to share code with the incoming CLI without importing from a Next.js context. This was not a single rewrite commit — it was a rolling migration over two months, with the old app shrinking as packages grew.\n\n**Jest → Vitest (Jun 2025):** factory-app's test infrastructure was migrated from Jest to Vitest in June 2025. The CLI was built from the start on a mix of Bun test and Vitest; the migration aligned the main app with the newer toolchain.\n\n**Assembly V2 → Assembly V3 / Vite rewrite (Oct 2025):** The original frontend was a Next.js app (`apps/factory-app`). Assembly V3 was a fresh `apps/web` application built on Vite + React, launched in Oct 2025. The two codebases coexisted temporarily — `apps/factory-app` continued as the backend API layer and was eventually renamed `apps/backend` in Jan 2026. The React compiler was adopted in the new app, and `useMemo`/`useCallback` were banned in favor of compiler-managed memoization.\n\n**Auth centralization (Feb 2026):** Auth logic was scattered across `apps/cli`, `apps/desktop`, and `apps/daemon` with duplicated storage and token management. In Feb 2026, `packages/runtime/auth` was introduced as a unified auth package, and a rolling refactor integrated it across CLI, desktop, daemon, and computers/sandboxes paths.\n\n**Ink dependency removal from agent core (Mar 2026):** The CLI's agent core (`packages/droid-core`) originally had a dependency on Ink (the React-for-terminals library). In Mar 2026 this was removed so that droid-core could be used in headless contexts (like the headless workspace binary) without pulling in terminal rendering code.\n\n---\n\n## Growth Trajectory\n\nThe codebase started with 16 commits in its first partial month (Sep 2024) and averaged 350–400/month through late 2024 and early 2025. The inflection point came with the CLI:\n\n| Period | Monthly commits (approx.) | Notable additions |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sep 2024 | 16 | First commit; Next.js bootstrap |\n| Oct–Nov 2024 | 300–320 | Sessions, Blueprints, Zoekt, Claude, Weaviate |\n| Dec 2024 | 427 | Prompt caching, o1 fixes, WorkOS |\n| Jan–Mar 2025 | 370–405 | Droid Mode, MCP, release 1.3.x cadence |\n| Apr–Jun 2025 | 315–480 | Package extraction, UI split, monorepo formation |\n| Jul–Aug 2025 | 527–637 | factory-cli initialized, droid-core extracted, Spec Mode |\n| Sep 2025 | 741 | BYOK, release ~1.3.200 range, highest month ever |\n| Oct–Nov 2025 | 610–548 | Assembly V3, daemon, desktop, Electron auto-updates |\n| Dec 2025 | 501 | Admin app, environment package |\n| Jan–Feb 2026 | 522–556 | Renames, Missions/Colossus, relay, signal, wiki |\n| Mar 2026 | 283 (partial) | E2B computers, worktree support, CJK i18n |\n\n**App additions over time:**\n\n- `apps/factory-app` (original Next.js monolith) — present from first commit, renamed `apps/backend` Jan 2026\n- `apps/factory-cli` — Jul 2025, renamed `apps/cli` Jan 2026\n- `apps/web` — Oct 2025 (Assembly V3, Vite+React)\n- `apps/desktop` — Oct 2025 (Electron)\n- `apps/daemon` — Oct 2025 (factoryd)\n- `apps/admin` — Dec 2025\n- `apps/relay` — Feb 2026\n- `apps/signal` — Feb 2026\n\n**Package additions over time:**\n\n- `packages/eslint-config`, `packages/logging`, `packages/services`, `packages/utils`, `packages/models` — Apr 2025\n- `packages/droid-core` — Jul 2025\n- `packages/common` — Aug 2025\n- `packages/core-ui`, `packages/frontend`, `packages/droid-sdk`, `packages/daemon-core`, `packages/daemon-client` — Oct 2025\n- `packages/updater` — Nov 2025\n- `packages/environment` — Dec 2025\n- `packages/runtime` — Feb 2026\n- `packages/signal-core` — Feb 2026\n\nThe PR numbering provides another lens: PR #1 in Oct 2024, PR #1525 for release 1.3.0 in Jan 2025, PR #4498 for factory-cli init in Jul 2025, PR #6737 for Assembly V3 init in Oct 2025, PR #9108 for Colossus V0 in Jan 2026, PR #10000+ range by Feb 2026. Over 10,000 PRs in roughly 16 months.\n",
