            "content": "# Fun facts\n\nA few things worth knowing about the Factory codebase that do not fit neatly into other pages.\n\n## The largest file\n\n`apps/cli/src/app.tsx` is approximately 160KB of TypeScript/JSX. It is the TUI root component for the Droid CLI and contains the full interactive session UI. It is likely the single largest source file in the repo by a wide margin.\n\n## The CLI is a React app\n\nThe Droid CLI is a full React application running in the terminal, rendered by Ink. Components return `<Box>` and `<Text>` instead of `<div>` and `<span>`, but the mental model is the same: hooks, context, state, and component composition.\n\n## Three Reacts in one repo\n\nThe monorepo runs React in three different renderers:\n1. **react-dom** in the web and desktop renderer (browser)\n2. **Ink** in the CLI (terminal)\n3. **react-dom** again in the Electron main window (desktop, same as web)\n\n## The name \"factoryd\"\n\nThe daemon binary is called `factoryd`, following the Unix convention of appending \"d\" to daemon process names (like `sshd`, `httpd`, `systemd`).\n\n## ~95 CLI commands\n\nThe `apps/cli/src/commands/` directory contains around 95 command files. The CLI went from a simple `droid exec` to a full-featured tool with commands for MCP management, missions, wiki uploads, SSH, diagnostics, and more.\n\n## Bun and Node side by side\n\nThe CLI and daemon run on Bun for its fast startup and single-executable support. The backend and admin run on Node.js via Next.js. Both coexist in the same monorepo, sharing packages compiled to work with either runtime.\n\n## The dev command that does not dev\n\nRunning `npm run dev` at the repo root prints an error message telling you to use `npm run dev:web` or `npm run dev:desktop` instead. It is disabled on purpose to prevent accidentally starting all 20+ apps.\n",
