            "content": "# Complexity hotspots\n\nThis page lists the files that are most likely to slow down contributors: either because they're very large, or because they change frequently enough that conflicts are common.\n\n## Largest source files\n\nThese are all candidates for splitting. The test files in particular are hard to navigate and often contain duplicated setup code.\n\n| File | Lines | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `packages/daemon-core/src/server/handlers/droid-request-handler.test.ts` | 11,857 | 2.4× larger than the file it tests |\n| `apps/cli/src/exec/streamingJsonRpcExecRunner.test.ts` | 5,457 | |\n| `apps/cli/src/services/SessionService.test.ts` | 5,116 | |\n| `packages/daemon-core/src/server/handlers/droid-request-handler.ts` | 4,994 | Central request handler; handles all tool dispatching |\n| `apps/cli/src/app.tsx` | 4,556 | Root CLI component; high churn (see below) |\n| `packages/services/src/settings/SettingsManager.test.ts` | 3,890 | |\n| `packages/frontend/src/services/session/DaemonSessionController.test.ts` | 3,791 | |\n| `apps/cli/src/services/SessionService.ts` | 3,579 | High churn (see below) |\n| `apps/cli/src/skills/builtin/constants.ts` | 3,409 | Mostly static data; could be split by skill category |\n\n`droid-request-handler.test.ts` and `droid-request-handler.ts` are the biggest split candidates. The handler has grown to cover every tool type; extracting handlers into per-tool files would make it easier to test and modify in isolation.\n\n## High-churn files (last 90 days)\n\nThese files change often, which creates merge conflicts and raises the cost of touching related code.\n\n| File | Changes (90 days) |\n|---|---|\n| `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` | 78 |\n| `apps/cli/src/app.tsx` | 63 |\n| `apps/cli/src/services/SessionService.ts` | 55 |\n\n`feature-flags/constants.ts` changes because every new flag is appended there. It's a natural churn point and hard to avoid without a different flag management strategy.\n\n`app.tsx` and `SessionService.ts` are both large and frequently modified. Any change to session lifecycle, streaming behavior, or UI rendering tends to touch both. Splitting them would reduce the blast radius of changes and make pull requests easier to review.\n\n## CI/CD surface\n\nThe `.github/workflows/` directory contains **53 workflow files** covering unit tests, E2E tests, lint, type-checking, CLI/daemon/desktop releases, web deploys, infrastructure provisioning, PR convention enforcement, and automated eval runs.\n\nThis is one of the denser parts of the repo to navigate. Adding a new workflow is straightforward, but modifying an existing one often requires understanding how it interacts with others (e.g., release workflows that depend on test workflows finishing first). When CI is broken, finding the right workflow file takes time.\n",
